<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Government to Create 2,000 Railway Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The leftist government of Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin has decided to create 2,000 jobs in the
state railway company SNCF this year, as part of its fulfilment of
promise on job creation during the legislative campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Transport, Jean-Claude Gayssot, who is from the
Communist Party, has made the decision after consulting with the
president of SNCF, Louis Gallois, reported the daily Le Monde
today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will reduce the 68 billion franc
deficit of SNCF by 20 billion francs (3.4 billion U.S. dollars) as
compensation for the cost of the job program, which will be paid
by the state by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Gayssot also has decided to maintain a decision made by the
former government and voted by parliament to open competition in
the French railway business by separating management of rail
tracks from that of trains, to turn SNCF into a user of the
railway infrastructures rather than the owner of it.
</P>
<P>
The rail tracks are now managed by the Reseau Ferre de France
(RFF), a state management administration which is in charge of
maintenance, construction and reparation of the tracks, while the
SNCF is only running the trains.
</P>
<P>
The reform of SNCF has met with strong opposition from some
unions, including the powerful and pro-Communist Confederation
Generale du Travail (CGT), whose secretary general Bernard
Thibault has asked Gayssot to scrap the reform.
</P>
<P>
The SNCF job program is believed to be a "token" given by
Jospin to his Communist allies, after the Communist Party National
Secretary Robert Hue had warned Jospin of not going back to his
campaign promises.
</P>
<P>
Jospin promised to create 350,000 public jobs as the most
important part of his campaign programs. How to apply this program
will be decided sometime around September after the Ministry of
Employment submits an investigative report.
</P>
<P>
The SNCF now has 175,000 employees, a clear drop from the
200,000 in 1991.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
