<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Votes Base Closing Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate voted Wednesday
to delay the next two rounds of closings of military bases until
the government can study the economic effect of past and future
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration had upheld that the closings of the
bases were key for the military to pare down defense budget and to
modernize the weapon systems.
</P>
<P>
The vote, 66-to-33, was seen as an ominous sign that
legislators were no longer willing to endure the political pain
for themselves and the economic pain for their constituents that
the base closings have sometimes caused.
</P>
<P>
It also revealed the doubts existing among many lawmakers that
the closings are achieving the savings that the Clinton
administration is seeking.
</P>
<P>
In its Quadrennial Defense Report released earlier this year,
the Defense Department proposed two rounds of base closings
between 1999 and 2001 to save 2.7 billion U.S. dollars a year for
the purchase of more sophisticated weapons.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives has omitted base closings from its
fiscal year 1998 defense spending bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
