<HEADLINE> Egyptian New Minister Denies Fire in Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Newly-appointed Egyptian Minister of
Public Works and Water Resources today denied that the fire which
broke out early this morning in his office was intentional, the
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Abu Zeid, one of the four new comers in the country's
limited cabinet reshuffle made on Tuesday, assumed the post that
has been vacant since the death in November of Mohammed Abdel-Hadi
Radi.
</P>
<P>
The fire had caused no casualties or damage to important
equipment and communications and computer sets, according to the
minister. But the fire completely destroyed the furniture of the
office.
</P>
<P>
The fire was quickly extinguished by fire engines from Cairo
and Giza after it broke out at 0400 (0100 GMT) today on the fifth
floor of the building of the Ministry of Public Works and Water
Resources at the Cairo district of Imbaba on the Nile bank.
</P>
<P>
The minister denied that the fire had been deliberate. He was
at his office until a late hour Wednesday night and when he left,
workers were cleaning the place.
</P>
<P>
Experts of the criminal lab have been examining the place
since this morning to determine the cause of the fire and the
prosecution is carrying out investigations.
</P>
<P>
Experts and technicians suspect that the fire was caused by a
short circuit.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's cabinet shake-up brought in four new faces and
changed the ministerial portfolios among six others, in a drive to
enhance the government's efficiency and speed up its economic
reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
