<HEADLINE> Rwanda Recognizes Joining War in Former Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman of the Rwandan army
today confirmed that Rwanda played "a major role" in the war in
former Zaire, by supporting the forces of Laurent-Desire Kabila
engaged with the forces of President Mobutu Sese Seko, according
to Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted Emmanuel Ndahiro, the spokesman, as saying in Kigali
that the Rwandan government has decided to recognize participation
in the war in former Zaire, because "the more we repel (an
admission), the more speculations there would be."
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Vice-President Paul Kagame told the U.S. newspaper
Washington Post published on Wednesday that the Rwandan army had
participated in the battles for the capture of several Zairian
cities, including Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Besides Rwanda, Angola, Burundi, Uganda and Zambia are also
suspected to have been involved in the war in former Zaire, all of
them supporting Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman refused to say whether Rwandan troops are still
staying in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRCongo) or not.
</P>
<P>
Some humanitarian groups have accused Rwandan troops, manned by
Tutsis who toppled a Hutu government three years ago, of
participating in the massacre of Rwandan Hutu refugees in eastern
DRCongo during the war, as 200,000 Hutu refugees are still
unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
The Hutu refugees fled Rwanda in the summer of 1994 after the
former Hutu government forces suffered a defeat at the hand of the
Tutsi soldiers led by the Rwandan Patriotic Front which is now in
power in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The Hutu troops and militiamen were accused to having killed
half a million Tutsis and moderate Hutus from April to June of
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
