<HEADLINE> Apple Computer's Head Removed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Apple Computer Inc., the pioneer
of the personal computer industry, announced Wednesday the
resignation of its chairman and chief executive, Gilbert F.
Amelio, in what was described a surprising move that cast doubt on
whether the company can be revived.
</P>
<P>
Amelio was hailed as turnaround specialist when he was named
Apple's chairman a year and half ago. Under Amelio, apple was
streamlined as operating costs and the payroll were cut sharply.
Yet, losses mounted as sales continued to fall. In the quarter
ended March 31, Apple lost another 708 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We've made progress in last year and half. But we're not yet
on a growth path and not on a path to sustainable profitability,"
said Fred Anderson, Apple's chief financial officer who will
temporarily take over while the board searches for a new chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
The abrupt ouster of Amelio is the latest unsettling
development for Apple. According to a report of the New York
Times, Apple's troubles today are a legacy of technological
stagnation, product missteps and management turmoil that several
rounds of layoffs and revised corporate strategies have been
unable to correct.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, Apple's share of personal
computer sales in the United States fell sharply, to just 3.3
percent, according to the International Data Corporation, as
computer users continued to shift towards machines that operate
using the Microsoft Corporation's popular Windows software.
</P>
<P>
The departure of Amelio did not mean that the company was
falling behind in product plans or that the company would shift
course suddenly, Apple's executives said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
