<HEADLINE> 5th Session of Bangladeshi House Prorogued today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The fifth session of the seventh
Bangladeshi Parliament was prorogued today after Speaker Humayun
Rasheed Chowdhury read out the Presidential Order of Prorogation
of the budget session.
</P>
<P>
Beginning on June 10, the session, which passed the national
budget for the 1997-98 fiscal year, also gave passage to one law
-- the Biman (anti-security) Offenses Act 1997 and introduced two
other bills for consideration of the House.
</P>
<P>
The session also witnessed several walkouts by the lawmakers of
the opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP).
</P>
<P>
The BNP also enforced a nationwide half-day strike on July 3 in
protest against the national budget placed by the government.
</P>
<P>
In his valedictory speech today, Deputy leader of the House
Zillur Rahman called upon the opposition to do constructive
criticism of the government to ensure better service to the
electorate.
</P>
<P>
He also sought full cooperation for the opposition,
particularly from the main opposition BNP, in the formation of the
parliamentary standing committees.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, deputy leader of the opposition Badruddoza Chowdhury
expected "a more tolerant attitude" from the government side while
conducting the parliamentary business.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the BNP would extend full cooperation in
making the parliament more effective.  
</P>
</TEXT>
