<HEADLINE> Britain Confirms Bosnian Warcrimes Suspect Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The British Foreign Office
confirmed today that Bosnian Serb police chief Simo Drljaca, a
warcrimes suspect, had been killed in a clash with British
peacekeeping troops who had come to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a Downing Street meeting, Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook said Drljaca was killed in the northwestern town of
Prijedor early today after he tried to pull a gun as British
troops moved in to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
Drljaca shot a British soldier in the leg during the operation
but the injuries were not life-threatening, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook also confirmed that another alleged war criminal Milan
Kovacevic, a hospital director, was under arrest as a result of
another separate operation.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very proud of the performance of the British forces in
this operation. They have shown very considerable courage. The use
of firearms on this occasion does demonstrate the risks that they
took," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These two men were within the British sector of Bosnia, they
were known to our forces and that is why they were apprehended,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether similar operations would be staged against
other alleged war criminals, Cook said: "Nobody knew of this
operation before it took place and nobody will know of any future
operation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
