<HEADLINE> Rescue Work Continues in Venezuela's Quake Wreckage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Rescue workers are searching the
rubbles of buildings in Venezuela's northeastern cities after the
coastal area was struck by a deadly earthquake Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At least 36 people were reportedly killed, more than 160 others
injured and thousands left homeless in the quake measuring 6.3 on
the Richter scale, the worst in the country in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers found more survivors today in the ruins of houses in
Cumana, one of the worst hit cities, local television reported.
But authorities said casualties could still rise.
</P>
<P>
Power, water and communication were cut for hours after the
tremor rocked Cumana, the oldest city in South America. Deaths
were also recorded in Cariaco and Casanay.
</P>
<P>
The tremor took place around 3:23 p.m. local time (19:23 GMT)
and the epicenter was about 49 kilometer off Venezuela's
northeastern Caribbean coast.
</P>
<P>
As six aftershocks were recorded later in the day, officials
warned that more earth movements could follow in coming days.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela suffered its last disastrous earthquake in 1967,
which was measured at 6.6 on Richter scale and in turn killed 245
people at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
