<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Ethiopians Get Better Reproductive Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Youngsters who constitute
about 35 percent of Ethiopia's population, are getting better
services especially in the areas related to reproductive health,
a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Negussie Tefera, head of the National Office of Population of
Ethiopia made the remarks in a statement to mark the World
Population Day which will be observed globally tomorrow on July
11.
</P>
<P>
Negussie said population and sex education are being given to
youngsters along with the formal education in a number of
elementary and high schools across the country.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, population and environmental protection
clubs where youngsters could freely discuss their views regarding
sexual behavior and reproductive health issues, have been set up
in many schools by the national office of population in
collaboration with the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs, the
Ministry of Education, the Ethiopian Family Guidance Association
and other non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
With regard to youngsters who are not students, the office is
striving to reach them through their respective associations,
Negussie said, adding that it has been also dispatching health
professionals to schools and various youth associations in
different regions to render guidance and counseling services to
the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
He further said his office plans to set up youth center in
major towns in the future to equip the youth with the necessary
knowledge on population affairs as well as social and economic
matters.
</P>
<P>
Youngsters are liable to various reproductive health problems
of which early marriage of young girls accompanied by several
negative consequences is the most threatening hazard currently in
the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Negussie said the other problem that puts the life of young
girls in jeopardy is unwanted pregnancy which often results in
illegal abortion, adding that the latter is mercilessly claiming
the lives of tens of thousands of young girls.
</P>
<P>
The theme of this year's World Population Day is ''promoting
the general condition and health care for the youth''. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
