<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Experts May Meet Directly: Pangalos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Greece's Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos today said that he did not rule out the possibility of a
direct meeting between members of the Greek-Turkish committees of
experts.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos's announcement came after Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel and Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis issued a joint
communique in Madrid Tuesday with the aim of improving relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"This is something which will become apparent in the next few
days, because up to now the Turkish answers have been very general
and did not create the conditions for a face-to-face meeting,"
said Pangalos.
</P>
<P>
The committees of experts were set up in May to examine
procedural approaches for resolving differences between Greece and
Turkey, but Greece later rejected a European Union (EU) proposal
calling on the experts to meet directly.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the committees exchange their study reports through
EU rotating presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
