<HEADLINE> Britain likely to Help Islanders to leave Montserrat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The British government may offer
people on Montserrat to settle either in Britain or in other parts
of the Caribbean if the islanders decide to quit the Caribbean
island, which has been ravaged by volcanic eruptions, according to
government sources.
</P>
<P>
International Development Minister George Foulkes was quoted by
Rueters as saying today the offer was being considered after
geological advice that the Soufriere Hills volcano could continue
to rumble for up to five more years.
</P>
<P>
"That means the south of the island will not be usable," he
said. But "As long as there is a significant number of people
wishing to remain, I am certain that there is a scheme that can be
implemented for keeping the north viable."
</P>
<P>
The British government is trying to "explore the detail of an
assisted package and resettlement grant scheme which could include
either the United Kingdom or other parts of the Caribbean," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Early today, Britain's International Development Secretary
Clare Short announced that Britain would give Montserrat 6.95
million pounds (about 12 million U.S. dollars) in an effort to
help the islanders.
</P>
<P>
"We are taking emergency action to deal with the crisis in all
its aspects," Short said, "We are also drawing up an urgent
package of options which will be put to the people of Montserrat
to enable them to choose the best future for themselves in the
face of this disaster." 
</P>
</TEXT>
