<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Boasts Highest Literacy Rate in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe now boasts the highest
literacy rate in Africa with over 78 percent of its population
able to read and write, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Gabriel Machinga said this has been
achieved through the government's concerted efforts to open up
more schools and non-formal adult education centers.
</P>
<P>
At the launch of a second donkey-drawn mobile cart library in
Nkayi district in west Zimbabwe, the minister said his government
has embarked on an all out program to make education accessible
to every child in the country since independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
''From 2,400 primary schools before independence, today we
boast of over 4,600. Similarly, secondary schools increased from
less than 200 to over 1,500,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
Machinga said while the country has succeeded in the
quantitative expansion of the education system, there is now need
to improve on its quality.
</P>
<P>
''One way of doing so is what you have done by making
available reading materials not only to the adult population but
to school pupils as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his ministry knows that where such libraries
have been introduced, the pass rates among school pupils is
improved, particularly in languages.
</P>
<P>
The mobile cart library was provided by the rural libraries
and resources development program which has 72 rural libraries
throughout the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
