<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Uganda Strives to Fight Famine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Facing a famine that is plaguing
half of the country's 45 districts, the Ugandan government has
strived to fight for secure food supplies since early this year.
</P>
<P>
A government statement made public recently said the famine
has threaten districts in north, northeastern and western Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Famine threats in the districts of Gulu Kitgum, Arua and
Moyo in the north and Kasese in the west were due to the large
scale displacement following the civil strife caused by the raids
of rebel Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) and the Allied Democratic
Forces (ADF); whereas the other districts were plagued by drought
when rains failed to come during the rainy season in March and
April this year.
</P>
<P>
Most people in the affected areas are in serious food
shortage, compelling them to live on grass roots or mango fruit.
Some even starved to death.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate human sufferings, the Ugandan government has
released 852 million Shillings (about 852,000 U.S. Dollars) to
purchase emergency food for the needy, and will allocate more to
this end.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that a total of two billion Shillings (about
two million U.S. Dollars) has been earmarked for famine relief in
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Y. Museveni expressed great concern on the
famine recently, saying if necessary, the government will use its
own reserves to ensure that the menace is fought and minimized.
</P>
<P>
The government has worked out a strategy to implement
immediate and long-term interventions to ensure increased food
production and security, which includes irrigation, use of
appropriate technology for production of adequate and improved
seeds and the enforcement of food by law by local authorities.
</P>
<P>
Internationally, Kampala has approached Inter-Governmental
Organizations (IGOs), Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs) and
United Nations agencies to help mitigate the effects of the
famine.
</P>
<P>
In response to an appeal made by Ugandan Vice President S.
Kazibwe, the World Bank has released 215,000 U.S. Dollars for the
purchase of seeds and farm inputs in the famine-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The U. N. Development Program has also committed half a
million Dollars assisting Kampala in putting in place an
anti-disaster policy.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the World Food Program has offered to supply food to
the displaced people in Kitgum and Gulu for six months and to
those displaced in the western district of Kasese following the
attack by ADF rebels. So far, 540 tons of food relief have been
delivered to the area.
</P>
<P>
Several NGOs, IGOS and U. N. agencies have promised to render
support in various emergency relief services of food, non-food
items, cash and agricultural inputs to Gulu, Kitgum and Arua
districts which are frequently being raided by LRA rebels.
</P>
<P>
With the above measures assured by the government, situation
in some districts such as Mpigi, Kabarole and Kasese has been
alleviated despite inadequate rains, although shortage still
plagues other areas.
</P>
<P>
Experts here hold that the long-term solution to the famine
which occurs nearly every year in the drought-hit country lies in
the creation of disaster preparedness and management commission
in accordance with the country's constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
