<HEADLINE> Al Chief Leaves for Lebanon to Inaugurate Arab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdul-Meguid left here today for Lebanon where he will inaugurate
the Eighth Arab Games Tournament.
</P>
<P>
In a departure statement, he told reporters that he will meet
with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi, Prime Minister Rafik
Al-Hariri and Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz on the latest
developments of the staggering Mideast peacemaking and current
drives to revive it in the light of Israeli intransigence.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Lebanese newspaper Al Nahar published
today, he pointed out that Israel now feels the pressure of the
Lebanese resistance against Israeli occupation in southern
Lebanon more than ever before.
</P>
<P>
"The Lebanese resistance should go ahead with its activities as
long as Israeli occupation in southern Lebanon is going on," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state has occupied a self-declared "security zone"
in South Lebanon since 1985 in defiance of U.N. resolutions and
stationed 2,000 troops along the border.
</P>
<P>
Meguid ruled out the possibility of holding an Arab summit at
the present, but he pointed out that contacts are under way within
this framework.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have called for holding such a summit to
counter the Israeli government's hardline practices in the Mideast
peace-making that has deadlocked for over three months.
</P>
<P>
The Arab leader also voiced his opposition to the Doha economic
conference slated for November, which would be the fourth Middle
East and North African Economic Conference if held.
</P>
<P>
"I do not believe in the so-called economic problems while
political issues remain unsolved," he said.
</P>
<P>
A number of Arab countries have decided to boycott the regional
economic cooperation forum which Israel is invited to attend,
saying that such a conference would only have negative impact on
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League said earlier that it has not received any
invitation from Qatar, the host. 
</P>
</TEXT>
