<HEADLINE> Russian Legislator: NATO Expansion a "Historical Mistake" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The expansion of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) is a "historical mistake," a Russian
parliamentary leader asserted here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The expansion will complicate Russia's relationship with the
NATO and its members, Sergei Baburin, deputy chairman of the State
Duma, or the lower house of parliament, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Baburin said NATO's recent decision to take Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic as its new members will make Russian parliament
more difficult to rectify the Start II arms-reduction treaty.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement made by the parliaments of Belarus, Latvia
and Ukraine, Baburin said the NATO expansion will pose threats to
European security and that of the world's other parts.
</P>
<P>
After the breakup of the Warsaw Pact Organization, the NATO has
lost its reason to exist. But the Western alliance still insists
on enlargement despite the end of the "Cold War," it noted.
</P>
<P>
The expansion will lead to a sharp increase of military
spendings in NATO countries, especially in its new members, and
make countries more difficult to agree on arms reduction, it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement also appealed parliaments of NATO countries not
to accept new members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
