<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor UK Parents Sacrifice to Bring up Their Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- One out of ten children in Britain
is poor as their families cannot afford at least three things most
families take for granted, such as three meals a day, a bed of
their own and shoes bought new and properly fitted, says a study
published today.
</P>
<P>
The report, by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation which tracked the
expenditure patterns of a cross section of 1,200 children,
estimates that the average cost of a child from birth to 17 is
50,000 pounds (83,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the difference between the better-off and families
without much income was surprisingly small as poor parents tried
to protect their child from poverty often by going without
themselves.
</P>
<P>
The survey finds that three percent of children are "severely
poor" as they lack at least five or more necessities.
</P>
<P>
As many as 85 percent of mothers said they sometimes went
without clothes, shoes, holidays or entertainment to provide for
their children.
</P>
<P>
More than a quarter, especially lone mothers on Income Support,
sometimes went without food to ensure their children had enough to
eat.
</P>
<P>
The key finding of the survey is that welfare falls far short
of even the most frugal child budget. For children aged 11, it
only covers 57 percent of the cost.
</P>
<P>
"This study makes it clear that policy makers need to improve
their understanding of what it costs to be a parent," says one of
the authors of the report.
</P>
<P>
The survey findings "also raise the question of how far it is
reasonable to expect low-income parents to make sacrifices on
their own food and necessities in order to prevent their children
from going without."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Population Age Structure Unevenly Distributed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain is increasingly divided by
the greying areas of retirement and the growing youthfulness of
many inner cities, according to official figures published today.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics says in the Regional Trends,
the annual digest of localized economic and social indicators,
that youthful London and Northern Ireland pointed to growing age
divide in Britain as the two areas have the least pensioners while
the Southwest and Wales have the most.
</P>
<P>
Compared with a national average 18.2 percent pensioners in the
population, London has 15.5 percent, Northern Ireland 15 percent,
the Southwest 21.1 percent and Wales 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that in contrast to the trend in the nation as a
whole, London's pensioner population will fall further from
970,000 in 1991 to 828,000 in 2011.
</P>
<P>
Figures also show that while across the country 6.5 percent of
the population is under five, in London the figure is 7.2 percent
and in Northern Ireland 7.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
