<HEADLINE> Angola Unified National Army Founded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 10 (Xinhua ) -- The Angolan government held a
ceremony here today marking the founding of its Unified National
Army (UNA).
</P>
<P>
Joan De Matos, Chief of Staff of Angolan armed forces said at
the ceremony that the establishment of the Unified National Army
has strengthened the country's armed forces by uniting formerly
waring military forces, and thus is a victory of peace and
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The new forces should safeguard national independence,
sovereignty and the unification of the country under the
direction of the Angolan government, Matos noted.
</P>
<P>
Blondin Beye, the United Nations' special representative in
Angola, said the founding of UNA is a victory of the joint
efforts of the Angolan government and the opposition National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
A total of 10,899 men from UNITA joined the newly formed
national forces.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the UNA, one of the most important stage in
Angola's peace process, started in December 1996. According to
the 1994 Lusaka Peace Accord, UNITA should have sent 26,300 men
to join the UNA, but the number was later reduced to 18,000 and
further to 10,899 as UNITA said it had not enough officers and
men for the UNA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
