<HEADLINE> Somali Salvation Council's Session Ends in Addis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The second ordinary session
of the National Salvation Council (NSC) of Somalia ended here
today, calling for the contribution of all Somalis to peace and
reconstruction in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing ceremony, current Chairman of the NSC,
Ali Mahdi Mohamed urged all Somalis to unite and leave no stones
unturned in order to realize the restoration of peace and
stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi said, the Somali people have experienced "the worst
human catastrophe in modern history of Somalia", adding that "it
is time for us to reconcile our difference for the sake of our
children, ourselves and for generations to come".
</P>
<P>
The second session called upon Somali brothers who did not
participate in the Sodere peace process to join in the council's
efforts of peace making and reconstruction of Somalia, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi requested the international community to continue their
efforts and valuable contributions to bring to an end the
prolonged and protracted conflict in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to the international community to provide
assistance, financial and otherwise to pave the way for the
convening of the Somali national reconciliation conference held
in Bossaso on November 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin said on the same
occasion that the NSC has, from now until the Bossaso national
reconciliation conference, to do whatever is necessary to bring
on board the peace process and all those who might contribute to
peace in Somalia and the national reconciliation in that country.
</P>
<P>
The recent Inter-Governmental Authority for Development (IGAD)
summit convened in Nairobi, Kenya, called upon Somalis "to take
all the necessary care to ensure that no one is excluded from the
peace process", he revealed.
</P>
<P>
The session was opened in Addis Ababa on June 25 and later
moved to Sodere, 130 kms away from Addis Ababa. 
</P>
