<HEADLINE> Mozambique Denies Providing Weapons to UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government today
denied that it had ever been involved in the incident of
transporting weapons to Angola's former rebel UNITA movement.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported recently that a South African
organization was delivering weapons to the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) via Mozambique's Nampula
Port, so that the UNITA could re-launch civil war in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the allegation, Mozambican Foreign Minister
Leonardo Simao said here today when speaking to reporters that
the Mozambican government had nothing to do with such activities
providing assistance to the UNITA.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted there were possibilities that some criminals
might have been involved in these activities, adding that the
Mozambican government was looking into this matter. Anyone found
to have been involved in providing weapons to the UNITA will be
punished by law, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
