<HEADLINE> Russia: Madrid Decisions Obstruct Ratification of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The decisions made by the NATO
summit in Madrid will make the ratification of the Russian-U.S.
START II strategic arms reduction treaty more complicated, Russian
State Duma Deputy Chairman Sergei Baburin said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference of Duma, Baburin noted that
NATO's decisions also complicated the relations between Russia,
NATO and its new member-states.
</P>
<P>
During the Madrid summit on July 8-9 NATO invited Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic to join the alliance, while NATO
and Ukraine signed a charter on special partnership.
</P>
<P>
"The new clouds in international relations appeared at the
initiative of NATO," he said, "it is not Russia that is erecting
this 'Berlin Wall'," Baburin added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Anti-NATO Chamber Alliance formed by Russia,
Belorussia, Latovia and Ukraine, in a statement said that they
would take every effort to refrain the NATO eastward enlargement.
</P>
<P>
A State Duma delegation, which mainly includes members of the
Anti-NATO informal group in the parliament's lower chamber, will
visit NATO headquarters on July 13, Baburin said. During the visit
the Duma delegation "will notify the bloc of the position of the
part of the Russian society which is against NATO enlargement," he
said. 
</P>
