<HEADLINE> UN Sanctions Against Libya Remains Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The UN Security Council
president said here today that the sanctions imposed on Libya
would remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
After the UN Security Council reviewed the sanctions imposed on
Libya today, Council President Peter Osvald (Sweden) said that
there was no agreement that the necessary conditions existed for
modification of the sanctions established in resolution 748.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions against Libya were imposed by the Security
Council resolutions 748 in 1992 and 883 in 1993 after Libya
refused to surrender the two suspects alleged responsible for
bombing of Pan Am 103, which took 270 lives on December 22, 1988.
Libya insisted that the trial of the two suspects should be held
in a third and neutral country determined by the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Agmed Esmat Abdel Meguid, Secretary-General of the League of
Arab States, and Salim Ahmed Salim, Secretary-General of the
Organization of African Unity, jointly sent a letter on June 27 to
the president of Security Council, requesting the council to find
a peaceful and just solution to the dispute between Libya and the
United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Secretaries-General urged the Security Council to undertake
measures to mitigate the severe impact of air embargo, including
exempting flights for humanitarian purposes, special flights to
send material assistance, flights for religious purposes; and
flights related to participation in official missions.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of France, Britain and the United States
sent a letter on July 8 to the president of the Security Council,
insisting that Libya must comply with the council's resolutions
before the sanctions could be lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
