<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Committee to Meet S. Leone Coup Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) Committee of Four on Sierra Leone, which
is in New York to brief the United Nations on the situation in
that country, is expected to meet the coup leaders next week in
Conakry, Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, as part of current sub-regional efforts to
resolve the political crisis created by the May 25 coup, will
give another opportunity for the coup plotters to ensure peaceful
settlement of the crisis, the News Agency of Nigeria reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The committee, set up at the ECOWAS ministerial meeting in
Conakry on June 26, is composed of foreign ministers of Nigeria,
Guinea, Cote d'Ivoire and Ghana. It has the responsibility of
monitoring developments in Sierra Leone and working within an
agreed framework to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The committee left for New York on Wednesday to seek support
from the UN Security Council for ECOWAS's initiative to restore
the legitimate government led by ousted President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah, after a meeting with ECOWAS chairman, Nigeria's head of
state General Sani Abacha last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The coup leaders in Sierra Leone, although facing
international isolation and domestic opposition, have showed no
sign to step down. Moreover, the military government on Tuesday
appointed a 17-member cabinet, which is seen by observers as a
step to strengthen control of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, troops loyal to coup leader Major Johnny Paul
Koromah on Wednesday launched an attack on the ECOWAS
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG controlling the international
airport of the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The attack was reportedly aimed at silencing a radio station
believed to be based in the airport.
</P>
<P>
It is noted that at the June 26 meeting, ECOWAS gave Sierra
Leone's junta two weeks to step down, or the sub-regional body
will employ embargo or even the use of force. Now two weeks have
passed and no ECOWAS action against the junta has been seen.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the Committee of Four's visit to UN
and the expected meeting with Sierra Leone's coup leaders next
week become the focus of attention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
