<HEADLINE> U.S. Suspends Aid Programs to Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced on
Thursday that it is suspending its 25 million US dollar aid
program for Cambodia as Second Prime Minister Hun Sen had
decomposed the 1993 elected government by ousting First Prime
Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came as Ranariddh urged the U.N. Security
Council not to recognize any government formed by Hun Sen and to
order a freeze on aid to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has decided to suspend our aid program to
Cambodia for 30 days while we conduct an intensive review of those
program," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a
regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
The suspension was "a clear signal to Hun Sen and his
associates that the U.S. will not be conducting business as usual
with those individuals," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
After 30 days of review, and depending on the circumstances in
the country, the United States will resume only those programs
that provide humanitarian assistance to the Cambodian people, but
the other part of programs that support directly or indirectly the
Cambodian government will not be resumed, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope very much that Hun Sen will reconsider his actions
... of rupturing the Paris peace accords and breaking the
coalition government that had been in place for the last four
years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Burns also said the United States welcomed the decision of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations to postpone consideration
of Cambodia for its membership in the regional organization.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very important act, which is exactly what the United
States had wished would occur," he said.
</P>
<P>
About 400 Americans have left Cambodia since the unrest erupted
in the last few days and there are still 900 to 1,000 Americans
left there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
