<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's police chief
today urged the leaders of both Catholic and Protestant
communities to use their power to head off the threat of violence
as Saturday's climax of Protestants' parade approaches.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone of any influence whatever should do all that they can
to urge restraint. That is what people of influence should be
doing from now to right through Saturday," Royal Ulster
Constabulary (RUC) police chief Ronnie Flanagan told reporters in
Belfast, the provincial capital of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Flanagan said he would continue to hold meetings with those
involved in the weekend parades but gave no sign of any early
breakthrough that would ease tension.
</P>
<P>
Protestant Orange Order plans to hold its annual parade on the
final day of "marching season" Saturday in Belfast and
Londonderry, the two largest cities in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
For Protestants, July 12 is the "glorious" day, the climax of
an annual marching season when Orangemen hold parades to mark a
1690 Protestant battle victory over a Catholic king.
</P>
<P>
But heads of Catholic Residents associations in Belfast and
Londonderry have called for mass demonstrations Saturday to
protest against what they say "are exhibitions of sectarian
triumphalism on their doorsteps."
</P>
<P>
A spate of car hijackings, riots and petrol bomb attacks on
police and troops dwindled overnight but police fear the potential
for a fresh flare-up is immense.
</P>
<P>
Five hundred more British troops are on their way to Northern
Ireland to reinforce the 18,000 already in the province and
12,000-strong police in case of renewed violence.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest RUC tally, 60 policemen and 64
civilians have been injured, 133 people have been arrested but no
one has been killed so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
