<HEADLINE> Mutineers in Central Africa Republic Return to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Former army mutineers from the
Central Africa Republic began returning to their barracks this
morning under the supervision of the Inter-African Mission to
Monitor the Bangui Accords (MISAB), said reports here today.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, by midday today, some 100 soldiers
were escorted from their stronghold in the southwest of Bangui to
their barracks.
</P>
<P>
The reintegration of the mutineers and their arms into the
country's army was set up in the Bangui accord signed at the end
of a series of army mutinies in the Central Africa Republic which
began in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
The mutinies ended on January 25 under the mediation of the
former Malian president Amadou Toure who is also chairman of the
MISAB.
</P>
<P>
The fighting in Bangui broke out again on June 20 as former
mutineering soldiers killed a Senegalese soldier serving with
MISAB. Over 100 people were killed in the clashes between the
mutineering soldiers and the MISAB and thousands of residents of
Bangui were displaced.
</P>
<P>
The latest ceasefire agreement was reached on July 2 after
Toure's mediation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
