<HEADLINE> Pakistan Diplomat Holds Talks with Afghan Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan intensifies its
diplomatic efforts for establishing peace in Afghanistan as a
senior official is to hold talks with the leaders of the northern
factions.
</P>
<P>
Additional Secretary Iftikhar Murshed today went to
Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 kilometers northwest of Kabul, to
discuss the proposal of setting up a political commission with the
northern anti-Taliban alliance, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
"I would inform the leadership of the Alliance that the Taliban
have responded positively to consider their proposal of setting up
a political commission," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He secured Taliban's agreement to discuss the establishment of
the commission during his visit to Kandahar last Tuesday
</P>
<P>
Murshed's visit takes place two days after UN Special Envoy
Nobert Holl's visit to Mazar-e-Sharif during which he persuaded
the northern Alliance leaders to come to negotiating table for
achieving peace in Afghanistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
