<HEADLINE> Two U.S. Leading Suppliers of Oil Drilling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. leading suppliers of oil
drilling equipment are planning to merge with a view to creating a
company large enough to build ships that drill for oil in deep
water, the New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Reading &AMP; Bates Corporation and the Falcon Drilling
Company, which are based in Houston in the southern part of the
United States, said that the merger would create a company with
the largest fleet of ships that drill for oil in deep water in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The deal comes as demand surges for such ships. Major companies
have begun to explore for oil in waters from 2,000 feet to 3,000
feet deep in areas like the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The proposed new company will have a fleet of 14 ships capable
of drilling in depths greater than 3,000 feet. There are only
about 35 to 40 vessels with such a capability in the world, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The new company would have a market value of five billion U.S.
dollars. The two companies have a combined workforce of 5,000, and
the sales of both companies have been up sharply in the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
The transaction will have to be approved by shareholders and
Federal regulators. The companies said that it should close by the
fourth quarter of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
