<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Producer Prices Drop in Sixth Consecutive Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. wholesale prices fell for
an unprecedented sixth consecutive month in June, the U.S. Labor
Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that prices charged by producers, such as
factories and food-processing plants for finished goods, edged a
seasonally adjusted 0.1 percent lower last month following
declines of 0.3 percent in May and 0.6 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
For the year so far, producer prices in the U.S. are declining
at an annual rate of 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decline resulted mainly from the 0.9 percent drop of food
prices last month. Beef and veal declined 1.5 percent as did
poultry. Fish, pork, vegetable and fruit prices all decreased.
</P>
<P>
But gasoline increased by 0.4 percent on a seasonally adjusted
basis. Natural gas was up by 1.8 percent and residential electric
power by 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the often volatile food and energy sectors, prices
inched 0.1 percent higher in June after two monthly declines. For
the first half of the year, they've declined at a 0.3 percent
annual rate after rising at a 0.6 percent rate during the last
half of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Inflation also was absent earlier in the production pipeline.
There was no change in the price of intermediate goods after four
monthly declines. Crude goods fell 3.3 percent, pulled down by a
15.4 percent plunge in crude petroleum.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the report on producer prices in June was
the latest reassurance that U.S. inflation was moderating.
</P>
<P>
The longest prior string of price declines since the government
began tracking producer prices in 1947 was five in a row, from
August through December 1952. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
