<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Changes Undertaken to Sharpen Singapore's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government today
unveiled a series of tax changes designed to lower business cost
and sharpen the country's competitiveness, in the face of
intensified competition in the region.
</P>
<P>
In his 1997 budget address at the Parliament, Finance Minister
Richard Hu announced, among other things, incentives to give an
added boost to the financial market and strengthen Singapore's
position as a major financial hub.
</P>
<P>
There will be a new tax incentive for Asian Currency Units
(ACUs) activities for an initial period of five years with effect
from Year of Assessment 1998. At present ACUs of banks and
merchant banks enjoy a concessionary tax of ten percent on income
earned from ACU activities.
</P>
<P>
They will also enjoy a further reduction in the tax rate to
five percent on the incremental income derived from certain
high-value added activities, he said, adding that in order to give
a further boost to ACU activities, the five percent tax on
incremental income will be extended to income derived from all
taxable ACU activities if the total taxable income from all such
activities exceed 50 million Singapore dollars (about 35 million
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fund managers who have substantial operations in
Singapore will be exempted from tax altogether for income earned
from managing non-resident funds. To qualify, they must manage at
least ten billion Singapore dollars (about seven billion US
dollars) of non-resident funds in Singapore and employ at least
seven professional fund managers and analysts.
</P>
<P>
They must also have a track record of three years operating in
Singapore under the Tax Exemption Scheme for Fund Management, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Income earned by banks and merchant banks from managing foreign
currency denominated Initial Public Offerings (IPOs) that are to
be listed on the Stock Exchange of Singapore (SES) are also
exempted from tax for the same period, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tax income earned by ACUs and Approved Securities Companies
from trading of foreign currency denominated shares listed on the
SES will also be exempted for five years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
