<HEADLINE> Situation Calm After SFOR Arrest of Indictees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 11 (Xinhua) -- International organizations said
on Friday that the situation in Bosnia has been calm since the
operation to nab war crime indictees by Nato-led Stablization
Force(SFOR).
</P>
<P>
SFOR launched the "Tango" operation in the Serb-controlled town
of Prijedor on Thursday morning -- the first of its kind since
being deployed in Bosnia, killing one former local police chief
and arresting the town's former major.
</P>
<P>
Both men were indicted secretely by the International Criminal
Tribunal for Former Yugoslavia for complicity in genocide against
non-Serbs committed in Prijedor during the 1992 and 1993 period.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, SFOR has deployed sufficient forces in
the region to monitor the situation carefully and to react
appropriately in any given circumstances, said SFOR spokesman
Major Chris Riley.
</P>
<P>
"There is no indication of problems in any part of the
country," he said, adding that the "situation in the ground
remains calm".
</P>
<P>
Alexander Ivanko, spokesman for the International Police Task
Force said that "it is business as usual" for the UN police
monitors in Bosnia, while local offices here of the UN High
Commission and the Organization of Security and Cooperation in
Europe said that their staff members have been adviced to take
certain precautions.
</P>
<P>
Riley insisted that the "Tango" operation did not mean the
change of the SFOR policy of not hunting down war crime indictees
but that it was done "when the tactic situation permitted, to
detain them in accordance with our original mandate and policy".
</P>
</TEXT>
