<HEADLINE> More Local Judicial Officers Assume Office in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Eight more local judges and
procurators replaced Portuguese legal officers in the territory on
 Thursday, marking a new step in the localization of law.
</P>
<P>
They are the second batch of local judges and procurators to
have assumed office so far, bringing the total number of local
judicial officers to 11.
</P>
<P>
The localization of law is considered a major issue in the
transitional affairs of Macao.
</P>
<P>
Before October 2 last year, all Macao judicial posts were held
by people from Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Macao top judges and procurators called the new move "a major
step" in the localization process, saying more locally-trained
judges and procurators will take office next year.
</P>
<P>
Judicial officials said 14 people currently being trained in
Macao will enter the legal service next year and 13 more will be
recruited for training in a training center in the territory.
</P>
<P>
By the time of handover on December 20, 1999, there will be
about 30 local judges and procurators in office.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the newly-appointed judges and procurators will
scrupulously carry out their duties and rights given by law and
serve Macao faithfully," said Manuel Antonio Maduro, president of
the Macao Supreme Tribunal of Justice, in an address at the
inauguration ceremony on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A commentary in today's Macao Daily News applauds the
inauguration of the new judges and prosecutors and urged them to
be prepared to serve the future Macao Special Administrative
Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
