<HEADLINE> German Inflation Rises to 1.7 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Germany's annual inflation rate edged
up to 1.7 percent in June from 1.6 percent in May, the Federal
Statistics Office said today.
</P>
<P>
In western Germany, consumer prices rose in June, the latest
month that complete statistics were available, by 0.3 percent from
the May level, amounting to an annualized increase of 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the eastern half of the country, prices climbed by 0.1
percent from May for an annualized increase of 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The statistics office said the increases did not mean the end
of price stability, and it should be mainly attributed to seasonal
factors and the current weakness of the German mark against the
U.S. dollar. 
</P>
