<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) today praised the Philippine government for extending
the unilateral suspension of military operations against it in the
southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, said
the MILF believed that the decision by the Sixth Infantry Division
of the Philippine Armed Forces to extend the ceasefire until 6
a.m. of July 15 could have been influenced by President Fidel
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
"We see this as a positive step towards the resumption of the
peace talks," Jaafar said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said the MILF has reciprocated the move by ordering its
forces to maintain a defensive position and not to launch attacks
against the military during the period covered by the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The military's Sixth Infantry Division Commander Raul Urgello
declared on Wednesday another period of unilateral ceasefire that
will last for four days.
</P>
<P>
Noel Detoyato, Urgello's spokesman, said the general was
encouraged by the positive result of the first ceasefire
declaration which ended at 6 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
"The condition is favorable so Gen. Urgello extended the
ceasefire to further support the peace mission by Mindanao
Governor Misuari and to complete the process for the return of
evacuees to their respective places," Detoyato said.
</P>
<P>
Misuari met with MILF vice chairman Hadji Murad Wednesday in
Camp Abubakar, Barira, Maguindanao province to mediate on the
impasse between the government and MILF's peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the MILF disclosed it will immediately arrange a
meeting with the government panel once the situation in central
Mindanao, particularly in Cotabato and Maguindanao provinces
normalizes.
</P>
<P>
The front also demanded, among others, the pull-out of military
troops from the captured MILF Camp Raja Muda and the return of
evacuees to their villages as conditions for the resumption of
peace negotiations.  
