<HEADLINE> UAE to Launch First Mobile Phone Satellite for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates is
closing a contract to launch the first mobile telephone satellite
in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
The Thuraya (Chandelier) venture, the owner of the satellite,
has set August 31 as the date to award the contract to the lucky
one of the three bidders -- Aerospatiale of France and the
U.S. firms Hughes and Lockheed, said Thuraya Chairman Mohammed
Omaran in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Thuraya officials have estimated the cost of building and
launching the Thuraya satellite at around 850 million
U.S. dollars, making it one of the biggest telecommunication
projects in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, to be put in orbit in 2000, will cover the India
subcontinent, Iran, Pakistan, Turkey, the Middle East and North
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The UAE's national telecommunication company ETISALAT owns 26
percent of the Thuraya project while the rest is held by other
public and private investors in the Arab world, Turkey and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Thuraya officials also plan to seek more investors to expand
the satellite's coverage range in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Coverage could extend to South Korea, Singapore, Thailand and
Indonesia if investors from these countries agree to subscribe
to the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
