<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Expecting to Collect 3.4 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government will
run a budget surplus of 4.8 billion Singapore dollars, or about
3.4 billion US dollars in the 1997 fiscal year, but will continue
to adopt a prudent policy in government spending, Finance Minister
Richard Hu said today.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the 1997 budget to the parliament, the minister said
prudence would continue to be the cornerstone of the government's
expenditure policy. It will concentrate on providing essential
public goods and services, consolidating the national economic
infrastructure and developing human resources.
</P>
<P>
He said such a focus will attract more high value-added and
strategic industries to Singapore. There will be generous
financial aid to upgrade local companies, train workers and
develop indigenous capabilities in high value-added skills and
Research and Development (R&AMP;D), he added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said that in order to build a cohesive,
resilient and gracious society, there will also be more funds to
promote Singapore's arts and heritage and on community and
sporting activities.
</P>
<P>
He said for this fiscal year, the government expects to collect
28.5 billion Singapore dollars (about 19.93 billion US dollars at
current exchange rate) in revenue, while spending is budgeted at
23.9 billion Singapore dollars (about 16.7 billion US dollars).
Hence, a budget surplus of 4.8 billion Singapore dollars (about
3.36 billion US dollars) is expected, the lowest since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Of this surplus, 500 million will be used to top-up the Edusave
Endowment Fund to its target of five billion Singapore dollars.
Meanwhile, 100 million Singapore dollars will be allocated to
Medifund to ensure affordable healthcare remains available.
</P>
<P>
As for pensioners, the monthly Singapore Allowance last revised
in 1993 will be raised by ten dollars to 140 Singapore dollars
from next month. The pension ceiling for those who can qualify for
the Allowance will also go up by 50 to 950 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, spending on economic and infrastructure development
will total four billion Singapore dollars (about 2.8 billion US
dollars). It will go to pay for land reclamation projects, grants
and loans to companies and transport improvements, he said.
</P>
<P>
Spending on security will account for about 33 percent of the
total budget and the largest share of 38 percent of the budget
will go to social and community services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
