<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Discovers Large Gas Field in Black Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A Romanian oil company has
discovered a large gas field some 160 kilometers off the Constanta
port in the Black Sea, Romanian press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Energy industry sources were quoted as saying that the gas
field, surveyed by the country's offshore petroleum company, known
as Scpetromar Sa, may turn out to be one of the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
Scpetromar has already sunk an 87-meter-deep well into the sea
bed to tap 1 million cubic meters of natural gas a day on trial
basis, and to help reveal the gas field's total economic reserves.
</P>
<P>
With a coastline of 245 kilometers along the Black Sea, where
the continental shelf is believed to boast rich oil reserves,
Romania began to tap the undersea energy resources in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, crude oil generated from offshore
fields has accounted for an average of about 12 percent of the
country's total output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
