<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Backs Peso Float </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today justified the Central Bank's decision to allow the peso to
move more freely against the dollar by saying that this will
preserve the gains of the economy in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"Together with sound fiscal policy and monetary discipline,
this exchange rate action reaffirms the government's commitment to
do whatever is necessary to sustain our economic growth, control
inflation and generate employment through, among others, the
protection of our international reserves," Ramos said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The action taken by the bank was not a "devaluation" of the
peso, he said, it just allowed the peso to "float freely" and the
bank just stopped being a market leader in buying and selling
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We also think that further intervention of the Central Bank in
the market is no longer necessary," the president explained.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the action will "protects the well-earned economic
gains of the Filipino people from the effects of the current
difficult circumstances prevailing in regional financial markets."
</P>
<P>
"As the Philippines continues to enjoy the benefits of being an
emerging market economy, the government will respond to the
challenge posed by its integration into global financial markets,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
