<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Order, Regulation Related to Public Service Gazetted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Public Service (Administration)
Order 1997 and Public Service (Disciplinary) Regulation were
gazetted here today, providing for continuity of the civil
service.
</P>
<P>
The order was made Wednesday by Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
under Clause 48(4) of the Basic Law, which empowers him to issue
executive orders.
</P>
<P>
The order replaces and localizes provisions in the Letters
Patent and Colonial Regulations, which lapsed on July 1, relating
to the administration of the civil service.
</P>
<P>
Tung also made the Public Service (Disciplinary) Regulation in
exercise of his power under the order. The regulation replaces and
localizes sets of disciplinary regulations and directions made
under the Colonial Regulations.
</P>
<P>
Both the order and the regulation are deemed to have come into
force on July 1 to provide for continuity.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the order, Secretary for the Civil Service Lam
Woon-kwong said: "Provisions in the order and regulation are
largely straightforward adaptation of corresponding provisions in
the Letters Patent and Colonial Regulations. They relate to the
authority of the chief executive to appoint, dismiss and
discipline public servants; to act on representations made by
public servants; and to make related disciplinary regulations."
</P>
<P>
"Modifications are made only in a few areas to ensure that the
final authority for the overall administration of the civil
service rests locally in Hong Kong and in the chief executive,"
Lam said.
</P>
<P>
"For instance, references to the secretary of state for foreign
and commonwealth affairs of the United Kingdom have been
replaced, where appropriate, by references to the advice of the
Executive Council," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The appeal channel for civil servants will also end in Hong
Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
