<HEADLINE> SAR Preparatory Committee Issues Press Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- A press communique was issued at
the end of the 10th plenary session of the Preparatory Committee
for the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) here today.
</P>
<P>
The plenary session was the last meeting of the Preparatory
Committee, according to the press communique.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen, chairman of the Preparatory Committee, presiding
over the meeting, announced the winding up of the Preparatory
Committee's work.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Shi, chairman of the National People's Committee (NPC)
Standing Committee, made an important speech at the meeting. Also
addressing the meeting were Lu Ping, vice-chairman and secretary
general of the Preparatory Committee, Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong SAR, and Rita Fan, president of the
Provisional Legislative Council of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reviewed all the work done by the Preparatory
Committee, according to the communique.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment in January 1996, the Preparatory
Committee has conducted a series of work programs concerning the
formation of the Hong Kong SAR in accordance with the related NPC
decisions, the meeting pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The work includes the formation of the Selection Committee,
selection of the candidates for first Chief Executive and members
of the Provisional Legislative Council, and the formulation of the
specific method for forming the first Legislative Council of the
Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Preparatory Committee handled some legal and
economic matters concerning the smooth transition, and made
preparations for the swearing-in ceremony of the SAR government
and the celebrations for Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
With the establishment of the Hong Kong SAR on July 1, 1997,
all the tasks of the Preparatory Committee have been accomplished,
the communique affirmed.
</P>
<P>
The meeting held that the return of Hong Kong to the motherland
and the establishment of the Hong Kong SAR are significant events
for both China and the rest of the world, and will surely have a
positive impact on Macao's return and the resolution of the Taiwan
question.
</P>
<P>
It also says that the "one country, two systems" policy is an
important part of building socialism with Chinese characteristics,
and requires continuous efforts of all the Chinese people,
including the six million Hong Kong compatriots.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
