<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E.A. Central Bankers Seek Common Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR  SALAAM, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Senior officers of the
central banks of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania have discussed
harmonization of the monetary policies of the three east African
countries within the framework of the EA Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In their joint position presented on their behalf by Mr. J. F.
Bossa, legal counsel of Bank of Uganda, the representatives who
met here on Wednesday, noted that the role of the central banks
in the three east African countries had significantly changed
during the past few years "from controlled to liberalized
economic framework".
</P>
<P>
Mr. Bossa said the new arrangements had given the central banks
greater autonomy which was focused on the formulation and
implementation of monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
To this extent, the central banks representatives said, their
organizations were well equipped to foster overall price stability,
facilitate orderly monetary and financial developments and thus
sustain high economic growth within the framework of the EAC.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Executive Secretary of the EA Cooperation Ambassador
Francis Muthaura said there was need to harmonize fiscal and
monetary policies in order to create an enabling environment for
the development of trade, industry and investment in the region.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura also told the meeting that the creation of a "uniform
incentive framework" would make it easier for "joint promotion of
the east Africa region as a single trade and investment area".
</P>
<P>
The consultative meeting agreed on measures aimed at further
streamlining and enhancing the effectiveness of the central banks'
role in the regional integration process, among them the need for
the central banks to institutionalize their regular consultations
and to focus their concerns on monetary policy issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
