<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Finance Companies Build up Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- After ten years of development,
finance companies have expanded into an important force behind
large enterprise groups in China and have become an indispensable
part of the nation's financial regime.
</P>
<P>
There were a total of 68 financial companies in China at the
end of 1996, boasting an annual profit of 2.78 billion yuan from
total assets of 82.5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Finance companies of large enterprise groups proved to be
useful sources of operational funds, which provide loans,
underwrite corporate bonds for the group companies, and clear up
debts among the constituent companies of the parent group company.
</P>
<P>
The finance companies are characterized by their efficiency,
and conducted a total of 169 billion yuan in settlement last year.
</P>
<P>
By serving as the underwriter of stock floatations, finance
companies also played an important role in the transformation of
the enterprise groups into shareholding companies, as well as the
restructuring, readjustment and trading of the assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Allows Peso to Float </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank today
finally gave up its efforts to stabilize the country's currency
peso which has been under continued speculative attacks since the
floatation of Thai baht on July 2.
</P>
<P>
The bank will allow the peso-U.S. dollar rate to "move within a
new wider range consistent with significantly changed market
conditions" as of today, central bank governor Gabriel Singson
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the move is expected to remove the incentive for
speculation against the peso and allow a gradual reduction in
interest rates more compatible with the economy's requirements for
sustainable economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The decision to allow the peso to fall was made Thursday night
in a meeting of the Monetary Board, the highest policy-making body
of the central bank, in the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
The move to leave the peso-dollar rate to be determined by
market forces will lead to an effective depreciation of the
currency, economists said, although Singson denied at a press
conference that the bank is "not really devaluing the peso."
</P>
<P>
Singson told reporters that the peso has been devalued under
current circumstances but he expected this temporary situation to
stabilize as markets are invariably self-correcting.
</P>
<P>
Singson said a more flexible exchange rate will conserve the
country's international reserves and normalize interest rates to
levels compatible with the needs of the fast growing economy.
</P>
<P>
Since July 2, the central bank had been forced to dip into its
foreign reserves and spiral up its overnight borrowing rates in
order to protect the peso.
</P>
<P>
Just on Thursday, the bank raised its borrowing rate to a
four-year high of 32 percent from 30 percent and vowed to "use all
available means" to stabilize the peso.
</P>
<P>
But economists expected the central bank to soon allow a slow
depreciation of the peso because it could run out of its limited
international reserves and a hefty interest rate will hurt the
country' economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine stock market today reacted actively to the
floatation of the peso, with its composite index (Phisix) soaring
189.99 points to close at 2,701.14 after having tumbled for four
straight days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
