<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels Willing to Resume Talks With Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) is willing to resume peace talks with the Philippine
government once the situation in the south is normalized, a senior
government official said today.
</P>
<P>
This was one of the points agreed upon by Nur Misuari, governor
of the Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao, and MILF vice
chairman Hadji Murad in their talks on July 9, according to
Presidential Management Staff Head Alexander Aguirre.
</P>
<P>
In his report to President Fidel Ramos, Aguirre quoted Misuari,
the rebel-turned-governor, as saying that "returning to the
negotiating table is not a problem to the MILF once the situation
is normalized.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Raul Urgello, commanding general of the 6th Infantry
Division of the Philippine Armed Forces, has declared a four-day
unilateral ceasefire effective today "to follow through the
momentum of the peace efforts."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Urgello ordered a 48-hour unilateral ceasefire in
support of Misuari's efforts to talk to the MILF leadership.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre, who was in the southern city of Cotabato on July 9-10,
personally talked to Misuari after the latter's meeting with
Murad.
</P>
<P>
Aguirre said the MILF was even willing to help Misuari in the
government's anti-kidnapping campaign if given the go-signal by
higher authorities.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Ramos instructed Misuari to "assume an active and
significant role" in the peace and development efforts in Central
Mindanao and to initiate contacts with the MILF to enhance the
momentum of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The president also directed Defense Secretary Renato de Villa
and all military commanders to extend their support to Misuari.
</P>
<P>
A series of kidnapping operations in Central Mindanao,
reportedly backed by some renegade MILF elements, prompted the
military to launch offensives against the MILF in the province of
Maguindanao and north Cotabato.
</P>
<P>
To restore peace and order conditions in the affected areas,
the MILF has agreed to vacate roads and highways provided military
operations against them are stopped.  
</P>
</TEXT>
