<HEADLINE> 140,000 Cards To Be Issued to HKSAR Civil Servants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 140,000 identity duty
warrant cards for employees of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) Government will be issued by the end
of March next year, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
They will consist 32,000 new Departmental Warrant Cards (DWCs)
and 110,000 Government Identity Cards (GICs), according to a
government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
All cards will carry the HKSAR's bauhinia emblem as well as
high-tech, forgery-proof designs.
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 DWCs and 30,000 GICs had been issued to officers of
five discipline departments -- police, Customs and Excise, Fire
Services, Immigration and the Independent Commission Against
Corruption, while the remaining cards will be issued before the
end of March next year, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
All the cards are being produced by the Security Division of
the Government Printing Department, with a total cost of 2.5
million HK dollars (320,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
GICs, in blue and black, are issued to civil servants who need
to identify themselves in their work.
</P>
<P>
DWCs, in red and black, are issued by discipline departments to
empower their officers to carry out statutory powers and duties
such as entry into premises and search or arrest.
</P>
<P>
At the back of DWCs is the extract of the law under which the
officer is authorized to exercise certain powers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
