<HEADLINE> Clinton Congratulates Poland's Access to NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton left
here this morning after a 20-hour stay to congratulate Poland's
fresh ties to the West.
</P>
<P>
Clinton chose Warsaw to celebrate the decision by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) to invite Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic as the first group of its new members.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski rolled out
red carpet for the arrival of his U.S. counterpart, who flew in
straight from NATO's Madrid summit, where the decision was made.
</P>
<P>
Polish press said Clinton came to deliver the NATO invitation
in person, and to notify the importance of Poland, the largest
East European country with a 38 million population, for the region.
</P>
<P>
The press also hailed it as a much needed visit for both sides.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Clinton talked with Kwasniewski and
Polish Prime Minister Woldzimierz Cimoszewicz, and then made a
speech in front of a flag-waving audience of thousands.
</P>
<P>
The Polish President, calling Clinton "an intimate friend of
Poland" and his visit a "historic" one, vowed to commit his
country to the responsibilities of a NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton warned Poland would have to face a heavy burden to
join NATO, including the costs of about three billion U.S. dollars
over 15 years for modernizing its 230,000-strong armed forces.
</P>
<P>
After Warsaw, Clinton was flying to Bucharest, the capital of
Romania, where he was expected to reassure that NATO's door would
stay open for other East European countries willing to join in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
