<HEADLINE> 32 Chinese Journalists Win Shapiro Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The third batch of Sidney Shapiro
awards has been bestowed on 32 outstanding young Chinese
journalism students, teachers and professional journalists here at
the China School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
A member of the Communist Party of Great Britain, Shapiro came
to work at Xinhua News Agency in 1950 at the invitation of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China. For the rest of
his life Shapiro worked as an editor at Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
His commitment to China's cause won him great respect from
Chinese leaders, including Deng Xiaoping, who praised him as a
sincere friend of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
After his death in 1986, Shapiro's family and friends
co-sponsored the Shapiro Journalism Education Foundation in London
to give awards to outstanding students and teachers at the China
School of Journalism and outstanding journalists working at Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Shapiro awards were first awarded in 1993. To date, a total
of 94 students, teachers and professional journalists have won the
awards. Starting next year, the awards will be granted annually,
rather than every other year, as at present.
</P>
<P>
Guo Chaoren, president of Xinhua, Liu Jinghe, Shapiro's widow,
and Solomon Shapiro, their elder son, were among those attending
the awards ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
