<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Sector Stable: Central Bank (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China's financial sector was
stable in the first half of this year, the People's Bank of China,
the country's central bank, announced here today in a news release.
</P>
<P>
"As the relatively tight monetary policy was conscientiously
followed and efforts were made to strengthen financial
supervision, the money supply grew appropriately in the first six
months of this year," the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that the outstanding amount of broad
money (M2), which is the combination of cash and all kinds of
deposits, was valued at 8,278.9 billion yuan by the end of
June. This amount was up 19.1 percent on last year's figure, a
growth rate 6.2 percentage points lower than at the end of last
year.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding amount of narrow money (M1), i.e, cash plus
demand deposits, stood at 3107.4 billion yuan at the end of last
month, up 20.6 percent over the previous year or 1.7 percentage
points higher than at the end of 1996. Cash in circulation, known
as M0, was up 19 percent year-on-year to 912.2 billion yuan by the
end of June.
</P>
<P>
The bank revealed that both deposits and loans grew steadily in
the January-June period, which effectively helped guarantee the
country's capital need for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June there was a total of 7,542.6 billion yuan in
deposits in the banking system, an increase of 597.4 billion yuan
or 19.8 percent more than at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that outstanding savings deposits totaled
4,275 billion yuan by the end of last month, up 19.6 percent over
the same period of last year, or 400 billion yuan more than at the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
As individuals held more cash in hand to capitalize on a rising
stock market in the early months of the year, and the authorities
took measures to prevent public funds being deposited in the name
of individuals to gain more interest, the incremental value of
savings deposits in the first six months of this year was 170
billion yuan less than that during the same period of last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Asian Nations to Step up Monitoring on Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of six countries in East
Asia today unanimously agreed to step up the exchange of
intelligence among their countries to reinforce their strength
against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Cambodia, China, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand,
Vietnam and the United Nations International Drug Control Program
signed an agreement on this matter during a ministerial meeting on
drug control held here.
</P>
<P>
The six signatory countries of the subregional memorandum of
understanding (MOU) on drug control concluded in 1993 also signed
a document to launch a training project for their law enforcement
officers in drug law enforcement skills.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the six countries also issued a Bangkok
declaration at the end of the meeting today, reaffirming their
determination to address the problems of drug abuse, illicit
trafficking and drug production in compliance with the U.N.
Convention on Drug Control.
</P>
<P>
The declaration urged those countries which are the sources,
transit points and destinations of chemicals used in illicit drug
production to pursue all means to tighten control on the
substances.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Sector Stable, Says Central Bank (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics show that the outstanding amount of enterprise
deposits surged 27.6 percent to 2567.4 billion yuan by the end of
last month.
</P>
<P>
The PBC said that the steady growth of enterprise deposits
indicates that the payment viability of enterprises has improved.
</P>
<P>
Between January and June, loans by all financial institutions
rose by 394.4 billion yuan, which brought the June-end outstanding
amount to 6815.5 billion yuan, or 18.1 percent more than a month
ago.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also said that China's foreign exchange
reserves have maintained a rapid growth since the start of this
year, reaching 121.2 billion US dollars by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
Though more yuan funds have been used to purchase increasing
surplus hard currency, the central bank has managed to control the
supply of cash, known as base money, by taking effective measures
to withdraw discount loans to commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the outstanding amount of base money
totaled 2749.8 billion yuan by the end of June, which was 19
percent more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The PBC said that despite all the improvement in the major
financial indicators, some problems still exist in the financial
sector, such as an unsatisfactory withdrawal of cash and
unauthorized borrowing of overseas debt in some places.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problems, the central bank will continue to
implement a relatively tight monetary policy in the second half of
this year and will take measures to curb cash supply and improve
financial macro control, the news release said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will also be made to rectify the financial order and
improve loan quality, in order to cut the ratio of non-performing
loans by two to three percentage points a year, the central bank
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
