<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Bourse Rebounds on Peso Devaluation Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine stock market today
reversed its downturn and shot up after the central bank announced
its decision to allow the peso-U.S. dollar rate to move to a new
level consistent with market conditions.
</P>
<P>
The 30-stock Philippine Composite Index (Phisix), which had
nose-dived in the past three consecutive trading days, soared
189.99 points or 7.5 percent to close at 2,701.14.
</P>
<P>
The broader All Shares Index jumped 47.67 points to finish at
871.09. All sub-indices were on the upside, with the
commercial-industrial and mining sectors registering more than
200-point rises after closing at 3,551.18 (+222.65) and 3,968.11
(+349.59) respectively.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover was 4.579 billion shares worth 4.2 billion pesos
(160.3 million U.S. dollars). Advances overwhelmed declines 118 to
13, with 45 issues unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts attributed the market's reversal to the return
of investors from the market of fixed income equities like
treasury bills after the announcement of the central bank's
decision this morning.
</P>
<P>
They said investors were pleased with the central bank's
decision, which will lead to an effective depreciation of the
currency and a lower overnight borrowing rate of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Investors had flocked to fixed income equities since July 2
when the central bank began to increase its borrowing rate to
protect the peso after the floatation of the Thai baht. As a
result, the Phisix had fallen almost 11 percent since July 2.
</P>
<P>
The overnight borrowing rate, which was raised to 32 percent, a
four-year high, Thursday by the central bank, is expected to be
lowered in the very near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
