<HEADLINE> Dhaka Stock Exchange Suffers Major Index Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The price index of the Dhaka Stock
Exchange (DSE) suffered a major slide in the just-ended trading
week as share prices declined further amid lackluster trading,
said stock market sources.
</P>
<P>
The DSE All Share Price Index went down to 1048.02 on Thursday,
shedding 50.33 points from the previous week's closing records.
Most of the traded issues incurred losses during the period except
on Tuesday when gaining issues dominated the market.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, a total of 180,747 shares and debentures worth
33.89 million taka (about 780,000 U.S. dollars) changed hands
while market capitalization on the day was 87.65 billion taka
(about 2.01 billion dollars). Both showed a downward trend
compared with the previous week's records.
</P>
<P>
The slide in share prices has been continuing since the middle
of June because the budget for the 1997-98 fiscal year was placed
before the parliament ignoring major demands of portfolio
investors.
</P>
<P>
The fall was precipitated last week when the Investment
Corporation of Bangladesh (ICB), the lone merchant bank in the
country, increased its lending rate to above 13 percent from 11
percent for the share investors' scheme.
</P>
<P>
Share brokers said investors had lost interest in buying shares
through the ICB due to the high interest rate. Unless a good
number of merchant banks in the private sector are set up, fall in
the share prices will continue for months, they observed.
</P>
</TEXT>
