<HEADLINE> Beijing Marks World Population Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition with a variety of
activities was held today at Zhongshan Park to kick off World
Population Day 1997, which is dedicated to improving reproductive
health and rights guaranteed by the United Nations Fund for
Population Activities (UNFPA).
</P>
<P>
The event was sponsored by several departments, including the
State Family Planning Commission (SFPC) and UNFPA's office in
China.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jieping, Vice-Chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, cut the ribbon at the opening of the
exhibition themed "Reproductive Health for the New Generation."
</P>
<P>
The China Population Publishing House presented a complete set
of "Family Planning in China" to several poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Jin Zhicheng, assistant representative of UNFPA's office in
China, read a message from Dr. Nafis Sadik, executive director of
UNFPA. The message said that the older people in society and those
responsible at all levels have a duty to care for young people and
should work for equality between girls and boys.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to let adolescents know that reproductive
health is essential for human beings, and to educate them to
behave responsibly," stressed Peng Peiyun, State Councilor and
SFPC Director, in a speech today.
</P>
<P>
She also pointed out that family planning, a policy carried out
to control the population since the 1970s, is still a difficult
and long-term task for China, a developing country with the
world's largest population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
