<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Cables Company Sells 51 Percent Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Korean firm, Dae Sung
Cable Ltd. has paid 1.4 million US dollars to Tanzania to buy 51
percent shares of the Tanzania Cables Limited (TCL).
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued here on Thursday, part of the
financial input will be pumped for production expansion and
modernization of the company to enable it retain its lead in the
domestic market and penetrate export markets.
</P>
<P>
Since TCL is a performing company, there were no issues of
retrenching employees or government absorbing or writing-off any
debts.
</P>
<P>
"The liabilities of TCL will remain with the company", said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement between Tanzania Presidential Parastatal
Sector Reform Commission (PSRC)and the Dae Sung Cable Ltd., the
Tanzania government has divested a total of 22 percent of its
fifty-one percent shareholding of the issued ordinary shares to
the Korean firm.
</P>
<P>
The Paper Products (T) Ltd., another shareholder in TCL has
sold 29 percent of the issued ordinary shares in TCL to the
Korean company and thus enabling the Korean Company become main
shareholder in TCL by 51 percent shares.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1970s, TCL is the first cable plant in the country.
It mainly manufactures steel reinforced aluminum conductors known
as overhead conductors for power transmission and distribution at
33 or 132 kv. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
