<HEADLINE> Australian Small Business Minister Resigns: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard announced here tonight the resignation of Small Business
Minister Geoff Prosser.
</P>
<P>
Prosser had been under siege from the opposition over
allegations of conflict of interest involving his substantial
Western Australian business interests.
</P>
<P>
Prosser's resignation became inevitable several weeks ago. As a
landlord of three major retail properties in Bunbury, he became
responsible for the government's response to a parliamentary
inquiry, recommending major reforms to retail tenancy laws.
</P>
<P>
In a minor cabinet reshuffle, the prime minister gave
responsibility for small business to Industrial Relations Minister
Peter Reith.
</P>
<P>
In his resignation letter to Howard, Prosser, who was appointed
as minister for small business last March after the coalition won
the federal election, said he had become concerned over the impact
of opposition attacks on him.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who has insisted throughout that Prosser
had not breached his ministerial guidelines by retaining an active
involvement in his business empire, praised his handling of the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
"In submitting your resignation you have placed the interest of
the government and the Liberal Party first and foremost," he
replied to Prosser.  
</P>
</TEXT>
