<HEADLINE> Singapore Economy to Grow by 5-7 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore economy will grow
by 5 to 7 percent in 1997, Minister for Finance Richard Hu said in
the parliament today, reconfirming earlier forecasts made by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Presenting his 1997/98 budget address to the parliament, the
minister said Singapore's economic fundamentals are solid, with a
robust fiscal position and sound economic framework.
</P>
<P>
With continued focus on staying competitive and responsive to
the external environment, the country can expect good growth over
the medium to long term, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Singapore faces mounting competition as international
competition is becoming keener in all sectors in the Singapore
economy.
</P>
<P>
Hence, the minister challenged firms like Singapore Telecom and
Singapore Airlines to move into new technologies, services and
markets and find ways to offer better services at lower costs.
</P>
<P>
The same goes for Singapore's manufacturing sector, he said,
pledging to ensure it remains a mainstay of the country's economy.
The future is not guaranteed, but it can be bright, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
