<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Industry Development in Inner Mongolia (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The electric power industry of the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region is using its abundant coal
resources, something that will help it become a major energy
producer for north China.
</P>
<P>
A modern coal industry has begun to replace the scene of sheep
and cattle roaming the vast pastureland for which the region is
known.
</P>
<P>
"The energy industry, which is focused on coal mining and
generating power will become one of the region's pillar industries
in the next five years," says Wang Suyi, deputy-director of the
region's planning committee.
</P>
<P>
This will provide opportunities for big energy consumers like
the metallurgy, chemical, and building materials industries, he
said, and the region should make full use of its rich mineral
resources for economic development.
</P>
<P>
It has more than 220 billion tons of proven coal deposits,
ranking second in the country, next to Shanxi Province in the
north.
</P>
<P>
Most of the coal mines in the region, with their thick layers,
simple geographic structure, and shallow depth, are suitable for
open mining, Wang noted.
</P>
<P>
With many state key mines like the Jungar, Dongsheng,
Yuanbaoshan, Yiminhe, and Huolinhe, and a large group of mid-sized
and small mines, the region plans to increase the output of raw
coal to 100 million tons by the year 2000, as opposed to the
present 84 million tons. About 45 percent of the coal will be sold
to other parts of the country or exported overseas by then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Industry Development in Inner Mongolia (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To ease the transportation strain, reduce environmental
pollution, and improve the economy of coal production areas, the
state has encouraged to replace the transportation of coal by
transmitting electricity.
</P>
<P>
The abundant output of coal and a relatively convenient water
supply has meant good prospects for the region's thermal power
industry, Wang Suyi said.
</P>
<P>
The region has accelerated work on three thermal power bases in
eastern, middle and western areas. Power stations including
Haibowan, Dalad, Togtoh and Jungar have already been built or are
being built around the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The power supply network transports 40 percent of the electric
power produced in the region each year to the industrial bases in
northeast China and the capital city of Beijing, where the energy
is in short supply.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the region will have a power generating capacity
of 54 billion kilowatt-hours, more than 40 percent of which will
be used outside the region.
</P>
<P>
The region has promoted the use of wind to generate electric
power. The available capacity of wind power has reached 15,000 kw,
ranking first in the country, according to Professor Wang Linjiang
of the Inner Mongolia Institute of Electric Power.
</P>
<P>
He says that some 125,000 small wind generators in the region
produce enough electric power for the daily needs of 560,000
farmers and herdsmen.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum exploration has also been done in the Urad and Ordos
in the western part of the region, Wang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
