<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Palestinians Wounded in Resumed Clashes with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 11 (Xinhua) -- About 13 Palestinian
demonstrators were wounded today in resumed clashes with Israeli
troops in Hebron, according to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian
press service based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The clashes happened in places between the Jewish settler
enclave and the Palestinian self-rule areas. Palestinian
teenagers tossed stones and dozens of fire bombs at Israeli
soldiers who responded with live ammunition and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. pro-peace nun stood in between the stone-throwing
demonstrators and the heavily armed Israeli soldiers trying to
calm down the situation.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Head of Israeli Central Command Major General Uzi
Dayan ordered the closure of Palestinian stores opposite Jewish
settlements at Beit Hadassah in downtown Hebron and an army post
was set up at the site, from where shots were fired at Beit
Hadassah Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
A pipe bomb was thrown at an Israeli army patrol near Yaacubia
School Thursday afternoon and five fire-bombs were thrown at
Israeli soldiers and border policemen during the day.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli authorities blamed the Palestinian National
Authority for the daily street battles in Hebron. But Norwegian
observers here said that the cause rests with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Israel's accusations, Chief of the Palestinian
Preventive Security Service Jibril Rajoub said: "My
responsibility is to defend my people and to ensure that they can
live in peace and security, not to defend the racist and
expansionist policies of Mr. Netanyahu."
</P>
<P>
"Half of the Israeli people oppose Netanyahu's settlement
policy. Why should I defend it," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
