<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Orangemen Cancel Parades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Protestant Orange Order has
voluntarily called off controversial parades in Northern Ireland
planned on Saturday to ease tension.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued late Thursday night, the Orange Order
said it was calling off the parades" for the greater good of the
province."
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday's march in Northern Ireland touched off a series
of violence with dozens of police and civilians being injuried.
</P>
<P>
The Protestants planned marches in Belfast, Londonderry, Armagh
and Newry on July 12 to celebrate the 307th anniversary of a
victory by Protestant king over the Catholic monarch. But the
parades were strongly opposed by the Catholic residents who say
the marches were an exhibition of sectarian intimidation.
</P>
<P>
The decision to call off or reroute the scheduled marches ended
a standoff between the Orange Order and Catholic residents
associations who had threatened mass demonstrations to block the
parades.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said the
decision would "be received with a great deal of relief and
appreciation in Northern Ireland and beyond."
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams issued a statement welcoming
the Order's decision to avoid possible further violence in the
province..
</P>
<P>
"I welcome these decisions and acknowledge their significance,"
he said. "I wish it had been made earlier." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
