<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,000 Lives Lost Every Year in Zambia's Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- About 1,000 Zambians lost their
lives in road accidents every year with a damage cost of 78
million U.S. Dollars, said a document on road sector investment
program 1997-2007.
</P>
<P>
Since all vehicles in the country are imported, the amount
also represents the scarce foreign exchange that has to be earned
and spent, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The cost covers direct damage to vehicles, insurance, policing
and medical treatment, it said.
</P>
<P>
The document shows that from 1990 to 1995, pedestrians
constituted 42 percent of the accident victims followed by motor
vehicle passengers at 36 percent and motor vehicle drivers at 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
Causes of the accidents range from unmaintained and poor
roads to incompetent driving and road user carelessness, it said.
</P>
<P>
The National Road Safety Council is currently devising an
action plan to improve road safety and reduce road accident
fatalities by 20 percent by 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 Percent Teenage Pregnancies Unwanted in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- At least 20 percent of teenage
pregnancies are unwanted in Uganda, and 73 percent of Ugandan
girls have sex experiences at the age of 18, local press reports
reports said.
</P>
<P>
According to "The New Vision" today, research on adolescents
has put the percentage of unwanted pregnancies of teenagers at 20
to 60.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes the high rate to the fact that young men do
not want to shoulder responsibilities for their sexual activities,
thus leaving their sexual partners in troubled conditions.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, over 50 percent of the youths aged 15 already had
their first sex experiences, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Teenage births has caused 25 percent of maternal mortality
of the country. Many pregnant women in their teenage did not
attend medical care at all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani PM Calls For Awareness of Population Planning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif today called on scholars and other intellectuals to raise
people's awareness about family planning.
</P>
<P>
Scholars should carry out census to help the government handle
the problem of fast growing population, Sharif said at the
National Population Convention held here today to mark the World
Population Day.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern over the rapid population growth, saying,
"It's a serious problem for Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's population has risen annually by 3.7 million during
the past few years, according to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
If the increase continues at such a pace, the country will have
a population of 140.8 million in the year 2000 and 193 million in
2010, Shairf said.
</P>
<P>
"Such rapid increase would badly affect our achievements in the
economic sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that population planning in Pakistan is difficult but
not impossible.
</P>
<P>
Sharif expressed the hope that the convention would not only
chart out an effective program but also draw up a future course of
action.
</P>
<P>
"We want to build a Pakistan which is free of hunger and
poverty," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
