<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The report on the reform of France's justice system, which
was presented to President Jacques Chirac on Thursday, includes
recommendations which could threaten the freedom of the press. It
suggests that the press not make public the names of suspects
under investigation or arrest, until a court agrees to publicize
the case.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Former Prime Minister Alain Juppe had warned his successor
Lionel Jopsin on June 2, the day following the victory of the French
left in the legislative elections, that there could be a serious
slippage of budget deficit in 1997. In a note sent to Jospin, Juppe
said that this year's public deficit could well attain 43 billion
francs (7 billion U.S. dollars) -- which represents 3.5-3.6 percent
of the gross domestic product, if no measures were taken to stop the
drift.
</P>
<P>
-- Nicolas Sarkozy, the spokesman of the former government of
Prime Minister Edouard Balladur, was nominated on Thursday
coordinator and spokesman of the new leadership of the Gaullist
Rally for the Republic by the party's new president Philippe Seguin.
Former Interior Minister Charles Pasqua returned to the RPR leading
structure and was nominated advisor on reform of party statute.
</P>
</TEXT>
