<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Recall 50,000 Faulty Bikes in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Japanese bicycle parts maker
Shimano would recall about 50,000 mountain bikes in Australia
because of faulty cranks that may cause injuries, the company's
Australian importers said today.
</P>
<P>
Saus Pty Ltd. Managing Director John Bazzano said the cranks,
which connect pedals to the frame and chain mechanism, were fitted
on a range of mountain bike brands from mid-1994 to mid-1995 and
sold in Australia during 1995.
</P>
<P>
Shimano was recalling more than 2.5 million mountain bikes
worldwide because of the defective cranks.
</P>
<P>
At least 630 of the cranks had broken while in use in North
America, resulting in injuries, company executives said.
</P>
<P>
Bazzano said no injuries had occurred in Australia.
</P>
<P>
However, his company was organizing a voluntary recall and
owners of affected models should stop riding the bikes immediately
and return them to a bicycle dealer for free replacement of the
crank, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The crank can develop a crack and this can cause a failure
under certain circumstances and we're concerned that if this crank
broke you will lose control of the cycle or at least do some
damage to your body," Bazzano added.
</P>
<P>
The recall would cost Shimano "several million dollars " in
Australia alone, he said.  
</P>
