<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Bring Population Growth Below 1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government plans
to bring the population growth rate to less than 1 percent in five
years from the current annual rate of 2.7 percent, Minister for
Population Welfare Syeda Abida Hussain said today.
</P>
<P>
"The target is difficult but not impossible," said Abida at the
National Population Convention held here to mark the World
Population Day.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's population growth rate has declined from 3.1 percent
in 1991 to 2.7 percent at present, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
She added that political commitment is basic for making any
population program successful.
</P>
<P>
"Though Pakistan has one of the oldest population planning
programs in Asia, but the lack of political will did not allow it
to fully succeed in the past," she said.
</P>
<P>
Abida asked the government to double the present budget of 10
million rupees (250,000 U.S. dollars) so that the population
planning program could be expanded.
</P>
<P>
She also stressed the need for educating women, arguing that
studies have shown that educated women have fewer children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
