<HEADLINE> Russia, Chechnya Fail to Reach Oil Transit Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Chechen representatives
concluded talks Thursday on the transit of Caspian oil but failed
to sign any agreement, the Itar-Tass news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian chief representative, Deputy Secretary of the
Security Council Boris Agapov, declined to comment on the talks.
</P>
<P>
But the Chechen representatives blamed the Russian side for
failing to reach agreement.
</P>
<P>
Aslan Maskhadov, president of Russia's Chechen Republic, was
reportedly poised to sign three important agreements on customs,
banking and oil transportation with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Asked when talks might be resumed, Akhmed Zakayev, the Chechen
president's aide and head of the Chechen delegation, said that
"the Chechen side is prepared to resume the dialogue as soon as it
receives a corresponding proposal from the Russian side."
</P>
<P>
The Chechen delegation arrived in Moscow on Thursday and left
for Grozny on Thursday night. 
</P>
