<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Highway Sector To Use More Foreign Funds: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China's newly-enacted Highway Law
has standardized the fund-raising methods used by the country's
road-building sector and could help attract more foreign
investment in the field.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made here today by Vice-Minister of
Communications Li Juchang at a news conference which was attended
by over 70 foreign journalists in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, since 1985, when China accepted the
first World Bank loans for highway projects, the country has
constructed over 10,000 km of roadways, with total foreign
financing of five billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, the Asian Development Bank and the Japanese
Government are the main suppliers of funding for road projects in
China, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said China plans to introduce more overseas funds for
highway construction and foreign investment is expected to cover
10 percent of the total demand for funding by the highway sector
during the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, by the end of last year, all the
counties, 97 percent of towns and townships, and 83 percent of the
villages in the country had been connected by highways.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the total mileage of highways in the country
reached 1.19 million km, including 3,400 km of expressways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
