<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, July 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities agreed to hold a second round of talks on the Cyprus
problem near Geneva between August 11 and 16, reports reaching
here said today.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan opened the five-day Cyprus
talks between President Glafcos Clerides, who is also head of the
Greek Cypriot community, and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
on Wednesday at Troutbeck, a rural resort 145 kilometers north of
New York City.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan's federal cabinet was expanded today
with nine new ministers and four new ministers of state taking
oath of office at a simple ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The federal cabinet now comprises 23 members -- 16 ministers
and five ministers of state.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Pakistan has condemned those responsible for a
train blast in India's Punjab on Tuesday, which killed 34 people
and injured 67 others, the Times of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn whosoever has done it. In fact, being a prime
victim of terrorism, Pakistan will condemn terrorist incidents
everywhere," Pakistan's High Commissioner to India Ashraf Jehangir
Qazi told the paper here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- U.N. Special Envoy on Afghanistan Nobert Holl
today met leaders of the anti-Taliban alliance in a northern
Afghanistan city to try to bring the warring Afghan factions to
the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
As part of his mediation effort, Holl held talks with the
leader of Jameeat-e-Islami Burhanuddin Rabbani, reports monitored
here said.
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said here today
that the institutional reform of the European Union (EU) must be
pushed forward.
</P>
<P>
The future of Europe should focus on politics, said Dini. He
spoke after the reading of the report by the Committee on Foreign
Relations of the Italian Senate on the EU Amsterdam Summit, in
June.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
peacekeeping forces in Bosnia today killed a former Bosnia Serb
police chief and arrested a hospital director.
</P>
<P>
The police chief, Sima Drljacca, was shot dead in the chest in
a fish restaurant when he opened fire on peacekeepers trying to
arrest him, in the city of Prijedor, in northern Bosnian Serb
controlled territory. Prijedor hospital director, Micha Kraccev,
was arrested on charges of complicity in genocide against Bosnian
Muslims and Croats during the ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- First Prime Minister Prince Ranariddh of
Cambodia met with General Assembly President Razali Ismail this
morning on the current situation in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Prince Ranariddh underlined the need to
maintain the integrity of Cambodia in the context of the Paris
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States announced on Thursday that it
is suspending its 25 million US dollar aid program for Cambodia as
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen had decomposed the 1993 elected
government by ousting First Prime Minister Prince Norodom
Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came as Ranariddh urged the U.N. Security
Council not to recognize any government formed by Hun Sen and to
order a freeze on aid to Cambodia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
