<HEADLINE> Russia Supports Pak Afghan Peace Initiative: Pak FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Federation supports
the idea of holding intra-Afghan dialogue in Islamabad and
appreciates Pakistan's efforts to bring permanent peace to the
neighboring country, Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference at Islamabad airport upon return
from a two-day working visit to Moscow, he said, "The two
countries moved a step forward in promoting greater understanding
and cooperation to deal with the problem of Afghanistan, besides
other issues of common concern."
</P>
<P>
The minister hoped that the proposed regional conference will
be held soon as there is complete unanimity of views and take
necessary steps for establishing a broad-based government in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif will visit Russia in the
first quarter of next year, during which further headway will be
made in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Gohar also referred to the recent shuttle diplomacy of Pakistan
senior diplomat Iftikhar Murshed and U.N. Special Envoy on
Afghanistan Nobert Holl.
</P>
<P>
This was "helping a lot to bridge the differences and bring the
warring factions on the negotiating range," he said.
</P>
<P>
Terming his visit to Russia as "highly fruitful and
productive," the minister said the two brotherly countries have
once again tried to establish excellent relations.
</P>
<P>
During the prime minister's forthcoming visit to Russia, he
said. the two countries will sign about half a dozen agreements.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, there would be exchange of visits by
parliamentary, trade, cultural and media delegations this year.
</P>
<P>
A Pakistan parliamentary delegation is to visit Moscow in
September, he said, adding that the Russian deputy foreign
minister is also scheduled to make a trip to Pakistan by the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Gohar's visit was the first high-level contact between the two
countries after the government of Nawaz Sharif came to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
