<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 07:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Assures Egypt of Gas Deal Despite Russian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Israel has tried hard to assure
Egypt that its talks with Russia on purchase of gas do not mean a
drop of regional option, The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The issue emerged after a delegation of five senior executives
from the Russian-based RAO Gazprom, the world's largest natural
gas producer, arrived in Israel earlier this week to open talks
for the supply of gas via Turkey and an undersea pipe line.
</P>
<P>
It seems that the talks have cast a shadow upon the
three-year-old negotiations for the supply of gas from Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Originally, the Egyptian plan called for Israel to import an
annual 2.5 billion cubic meters of gas by the year 2000 via a
pipeline across the Sinai Desert. Now experts say a deadline of
2002 looks more realistic.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Israeli National Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon in the Knesset (parliament) Wednesday, Gazprom
Future Development Director Victor Brianski said gas could be
supplied to Israel by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the two sides will resume at the end of this
month or early next month. The Israel Electric Corporation will
become a major player in these negotiations as it will be the
major purchaser of the gas.
</P>
<P>
The idea of purchasing Russian gas was first raised by Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu under political considerations. During
his visit to Russia in March, Netanyahu suggested that Israel
spend billions of dollars to buy Russian oil and gas in return for
Russian cancellation of nuclear and missile deals with Iran.
</P>
<P>
In June, Sharon visited Moscow for talks with Gazprom and
senior Russian government officials following the appointment of
new Fuel and Energy Minister Boris Nemtsov.
</P>
<P>
In prompt reaction to the latest development, Egyptian
Ambassador to Israel Mohammed Bassiouny said that "the decision is
up to Israel." He added that Egypt will have no problems selling
its gas elsewhere, with the Palestinian National Authority being a
possible alternative customer.
</P>
<P>
Bassiouny pointed out that Egypt is next door, while Russian
source is thousands of kilometers away. "Of course the supply
would be cheaper from Egypt," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry sources were quoted as saying that
Israel will possibly buy gas from both Russia and Egypt so as
"not to put all the energy eggs in one basket."
</P>
<P>
Israel has also considered a deal with Qatar. But the option
seems less likely, given the high costs, with the need for a
pipeline through Saudi Arabia or shipments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0159 </DOCNO>
