<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Wants Better Compliance With Tariff Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand wants the ASEAN
Secretariat to take a closer look at the implementation of tariff
reductions under the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) in order to
guard against violations.
</P>
<P>
Six of the seven ASEAN members have committed to reducing
tariffs on a wide range of goods to between zero and 5 percent by
the year 2003. Vietnam has been given until 2006 to do so.
</P>
<P>
However, the secretariat has not been examining whether some
members were breaching their commitments, the Bangkok Post today
quoted Charin Harnsuebsai, deputy director-general of the Business
Economics Department, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Charin complained that Indonesia and Malaysia have increased
their tariffs on imported petrochemical products from 5 to 40
percent, but did not inform the secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Petrochemical products are on the "fast track" tariff reduction
program, with the year 2000 as the deadline for tariffs to fall
from an average of 20 percent or more to between zero and 5
percent level.
</P>
<P>
Thai economic officials may raise the issue at a meeting later
this month in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
The officials may also raise at the meeting the Philippines'
refusal to include rice in its tariff reduction regime. The
Philippine government sought a ruling from its supreme court on
whether it should reduce protection for rice.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat should have a transparent mechanism for
monitoring compliance with tariff reduction commitments, Charin
urged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
