<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Gives Priority to Population Control:PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has given
top priority to population control as the speed at which the
population is growing has posed a major problem, Nepali Prime
Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion of the World Population Day today,
Chand said that despite a decreasing fertility rate in Nepal, the
country's population was growing at an alarming rate of 2.1
percent.
He warned that it has become almost impossible to meet the basic
needs and social services of the population.
</P>
<P>
The increase of population has impeded the work of achieving
the target in every field of the national economy, the prime
minister added.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Population and Environment Vidya Devi Bhandari
said on the occasion that the government is committed to
decreasing the growth rate of population to the desired extent,
and to achieving sustainable development by raising the living
standards of the people.
</P>
<P>
The World Population Day is observed here today with the slogan
"The Right to Choose: Reproductive Rights and Reproductive
Health".
</P>
<P>
Nepal now has a population of 21.4 million. The figure is
expected to reach 22.5 million by 2000 and 30 million by 2030.
</P>
</TEXT>
