<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Of Flood-proof Dike In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Construction on a 17-km-long dike
has been going smoothly in Liuzhou, China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The 1.2-billion-yuan (150 million US dollars) project, which is
expected to be completed in three years, is designed to protect
the 29.2-sq.km. urban area and its 377,000 residents. It will be
able to withstand the worst floods in a 50-year period.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has allocated 100 million yuan for the
project, and the regional government plans to allocate 100 million
yuan each year for it.
</P>
<P>
By now, the project has received nearly seven million yuan from
all sectors of the local society.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the dike is partly completed, and it has
already played a role in stopping flooding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
