<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Leaders on Need to Check Rapid Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani leaders said today in
their separate messages on the occasion of World Population Day
that the population issue should be addressed with all
seriousness.
</P>
<P>
President Farooq Leghari said the population growth has a
significant impact on development efforts, poverty alleviation and
quality of life in Pakistan and it is important that the problems
are tackled effectively.
</P>
<P>
The target of bringing down the population growth from 2.9
percent to 2.6 percent during the eighth Five Year Plan (1993-98)
would largely depend on awareness about family planning, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This should be backed up by focusing attention on the needs of
our rural population and providing them quality family planning
services at their door steps," Leghari added.
</P>
<P>
The president also said that if the government has to succeed
in its efforts of providing food, housing, health care services
and education to the masses, it must first control the rapid rate
of population growth.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said in his message that
demographic details for Pakistan are not much different from other
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"We are the seventh most populous country in the world," said
Sharif.
</P>
<P>
He said the task of population control in the country requires
extraordinary efforts, dedication and involvement of public and
private sector organizations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the initiatives taken by the Ministry of
Population Welfare to popularize the concept of small family norm
are now steadily taking roots in the society and some positive
results have emerged.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Sharif said, Pakistan's population growth rate has
come down to 2.7 percent per annum and is expected to further be
reduced to 1.7 percent by the end of the Ninth Five Year Plan
(1998-2003).
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said population issues demand urgent
attention as decisions taken today in this direction will shape
Pakistan's future.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said high rate of population growth is casting adverse
affects on key components of social sector, notably health,
education and employment.
</P>
<P>
"If we were to make sustainable development, then this problem
needs to be addressed effectively," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on the nation to come forward and supplement
government's efforts to make Pakistan a prosperous and stable
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
