<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Sugar Exports Suffer From Low World Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- India's sugar exports in the
1996-97 (October-September) season dropped to a trickle due to low
world prices, the Times of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
"International sugar prices are so low that our prices are not
competitive in the market," said a senior official of India's
Agricultural and Processed Food Products Export Development
Authority (APEDA).
</P>
<P>
APEDA, which was authorized by the Indian Food Ministry to
export 250,000 tons of sugar in the 1996-97 season, has so far
issued licenses for the export of about 210,000 tons but actual
exports are much lower, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"Only 50,000 tons have actually exported, 90 percent of it to
Pakistan by rail," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said small quantities had been shipped to Singapore, the
Maldives and Canada.  
</P>
</TEXT>
