<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Rise in Thailand on Fall of Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Most oil companies in Thailand
began on Thursday to raise retail oil prices to correspond with
the new exchange rate, which has gone up from about 25.80 baht to
the dollar 10 days ago to about 29.
</P>
<P>
Major oil firms such as Esso, Shell and Caltex raised their
pump prices by 18 satang (one baht has 100 satang) per liter for
all types of gasoline and diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
As of Thursday, the state-owned Petroleum Authority of Thailand
and partly state-owned Bangchak Petroleum maintained their prices
at the June 26 level, the last time the prices were adjusted.
</P>
<P>
Petroleum Authority of Thailand officials say that their
service stations would raise pump prices on Saturday by a margin
of 15 satang a liter.
</P>
<P>
Oil firms are expected to further raise pump prices by mid next
week, probably by 10-20 satang per liter, "to cover up higher
costs" because of the baht flotation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
