<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Chinese County Benefits From World Food Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The lives of over 100,000 peasants
in Linxian county, the largest poverty-stricken area in North
China's Shanxi province, have improved immensely thanks to an
aid-the-poor project sponsored by the World Food Program (WFP).
</P>
<P>
Linxian county is a mountainous area with a population of over
500,000 and is one of the major targets of poverty relief of
China's State Council.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the WFP began its project there by fighting
soil-erosion. And by the first half of this year, farmers
benefitted from the project and now have an average per capita
income of 620 yuan a year, nearly double that of five years
ago. This means that they now also have sufficient food and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
The project also helped develop forests, harness rivers,
improve farmland and roads, and spread the use of agro-technology
among the peasants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flash Flood Hits Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rain for the past three
days has caused flash floods in several districts around
Bangladesh, leaving tens of thousands of people marooned.
</P>
<P>
Road links between Chittagong City and the Cox's Bazar were cut
off from Thursday morning as flood waters submerged several
portions of the highway, according to the local press today.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that about 0.4 million people in three counties
of the Cox's Bazar district were marooned while thousands of
houses were affected by the flood waters. People were using boats
as the only means of transportation.
</P>
<P>
In the hill districts, some 75,000 people were stranded due to
the downpour and a deluge from neighboring India. Road links
within the three hill districts will also snap if the rain
continues.
</P>
<P>
The flood also inundated the low-lying areas of at least three
counties in the northeastern Sylhet district. Standing crops and
seed beds on 6,000 acres (about 2,000 hectares) of land were
washed away by the water from the hills.
</P>
<P>
In the northwestern Durigram district, the water level of all
the rivers have recorded a sharp rise and the devastating erosion
by the three major rivers has already made 12,000 people homeless.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bangladesh Water Development Board, about 10
districts around the country suffered flood because of incessant
rain. The meteorological office also forecast heavy to very heavy
rainfall at places all over the country until tomorrow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
