<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Holds Talks With Anti-Taliban Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Special Envoy on
Afghanistan Nobert Holl today met leaders of the anti-Taliban
alliance in a northern Afghanistan city to try to bring the
warring Afghan factions to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
As part of his mediation effort, Holl, who arrived in
Mazar-e-Sharif earlier today, held talks with the leader of
Jameeat-e-Islami Burhanuddin Rabbani, reports monitored here said.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on persuading all the factions to hold
negotiations for moving toward setting up a broad-based government
in the war-torn country, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The reports added that Holl also held talks with other
Jameeat-e-Islami leaders, centering around prospects of peace in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Holl also had talks with Abdul Malik, leader of the
National Islamic Movement, and discussed with him ways for a
cease-fire between the Taliban and its opponents.
</P>
<P>
Matters concerning a future Afghan government was also under
discussion, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
"New efforts have to be undertaken to stop bloodshed and to
bring both sides together under the auspices of the United
Nations," Holl was quoted as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
