<HEADLINE> Pakistan Envoy Condemns Train Blast in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has condemned people
responsible for a train blast in India's Punjab on Tuesday which
killed 34 people and injured 67 others, the Times of India
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn whosoever has done it. In fact, being a prime
victim of terrorism, Pakistan will condemn terrorist incidents
everywhere," Pakistan's High Commissioner to India Ashraf Jehangir
Qazi told the paper here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Qazi made the statement in response to Punjab Chief Minister
Prakash Singh Badal's remarks on Wednesday that Pakistan's
Inter-Services Intelligence was behind the blast.
</P>
<P>
The envoy said the allegation was regrettable at a time when
the political leaders of both countries were deeply committed to
improving bilateral ties in the 50th year of independence of the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The envoy stressed that the two sides should discourage hostile
propaganda against each other, as understood during last month's
foreign secretary-level talks in Islamabad between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the two sides had also agreed to put
terrorism-confronting on the agenda of Indo-Pakistan dialogue.
</P>
</TEXT>
