<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Seeking Closer Ties With Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan Province
will try to expand trade and economic cooperation with Hong Kong,
Governor Ma Zhongcheng said recently.
</P>
<P>
The province would like to use investment, technology and
management expertise from Hong Kong to increase the economic
growth of Henan, the country's most populous province, he added.
</P>
<P>
The governor emphasized that economic and trade affairs must
strictly comply with the Basic Law of Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), but that prospects for cooperation
in developing agriculture, mineral resources, tourism, and
industrial enterprises are good.
</P>
<P>
In agriculture, Henan can use investment and technology from
Hong Kong to improve its farm produce and sideline products at
more efficient agricultural production bases, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, by the end of the 1991-95
period, Henan had 1.8 billion U.S. dollars in exports, some 600
million U.S. dollars of which were shipped to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Investment from Hong Kong has accounted for 66.6 percent of the
1.92 billion U.S. dollars worth of overseas investment in the
province. It has plans for infrastructure construction, in hopes
of becoming a transit center for commodities from interior areas
to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Henan has been used more frequently as a transit point since
the establishment of the Eurasian Continental Bridge, and is
connected to Hong Kong by the Beijing-Kowloon Railway Line, the
Beijing-Guangzhou Railway Line, and the Beijing-Shenzhen
Expressway.
</P>
<P>
The province will improve management of the tourism sector,
develop tourist resources, and create a better tourist environment
to attract more people from Hong Kong, a local official said,
adding that an association for coordinating economic cooperation
between Hong Kong and Henan, and a regular system of visits and
meetings of officials at various levels is also being suggested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
