<HEADLINE> Car Thieves on Rampage in Lusaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Three vehicles, while parked at
their respective places in the Zambian capital Lusaka, were
stolen by car thieves on thursday.
</P>
<P>
While confirming the incidents, acting police spokesman
Beenwell Chifwembe said that all the three vehicles have not yet
been recovered but the Police Flying Squad is investigating the
thefts.
</P>
<P>
A Toyota Hilux was stolen Thursday morning while parked at a
house near University of zambia campus, another Toyota Hilux was
snatched around 17:00 hours in a township and a third vehicle was
grabbed from a motorist at a supermarket the same day.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a Zambia Daily Mail van was stolen last
week and later it was recovered by the Police Flying Squad. But
the car was found completely transformed and bearing a UNDP
(United Nations Developmehnt Program) emblem.
</P>
<P>
It is said that car thieves have become so sophisticated that
they use anything, including GRZ (Government of Zambia) or CD
(diplomatic) number plates to disguize stolen motor vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
