<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 07:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Settlers Held Protests in PNA-controlled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Some 20 Jewish settlers held
protests overnight at a road junction near the West Bank city of
Nablus, which is under control by the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the settlers, who were from Elon
More in northeast of Nablus, staged the protests after shots
were fired at the site on the car driven by the Rabbi of the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
No one was injured in the shooting incident, and it remained
unknown who was responsible for the attack.
</P>
<P>
The settlers demanded Israeli troops increase protection of
their security, saying they would stay at the site and even set
up a post themselves at the junction if the troops refused to
do so.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli undercover agents arrested Thursday night
four Palestinian youths near the Jewish holy site of Rachel's
Tomb on the outskirts of Bethlehem. They were arrested on
suspicion of throwing firebombs at the Israeli soldiers guarding
the tomb.
</P>
<P>
In another development concerning settlers in the Palestinian
territories, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu met with
settler representatives from Gush Katif settlement in Gaza Strip,
which was the scene of a series of fierce clashes betweeen
Palestinians and settlers and Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu promised not to remove the settlement in the final
settlement between Israel and the PNA. He vowed to increase the
settlers' security, saying he would pay a visit soon to the
settlement to show his support. He added that the talks on
resuming the Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation was in
high gear.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the recent tension in the territories and the
political turmoil in Israel over the cabinet reshuffle, the
Israeli government seemed to return to business as usual to
tackle the deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai held a
meeting with PNA Planning Minister Nabil Shaath at the residence
of Egyptian Ambassador to Israel Mohammed Bassiouny.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the two sides made some progress on the issues
of opening the airport and seaport in Gaza and the establishment
of safe passages for Palestinians traveling between Gaza Strip
and West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
