<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Part-Time Force Plans to Recruit More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The South African National
Defense Force will recruit more black members to join the
voluntary Part-Time Force (PTF) this year, local daily Sowetan
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Roy Anderson, Director of the PTF Brigadier, was quoted as
saying that his priority this year would be to attract more black
members, while at the same time identifying those with leadership
ability to use them as "role-models" for the unit.
</P>
<P>
South Africa currently has 48,345 PTF members,including 11,516
blacks, 4,277 coloreds and 213 Indians, while the majority are
white.
</P>
<P>
Anderson said the major obstacle facing his unit was the
yearly budgetary cuts, but he remained hopeful that the situation
would improve.
</P>
<P>
"We need to concentrate on advanced training as we want
quality rather than quantity," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Anderson, during a time of war, part-time forces
could constitute up to 70 percent of the conventional forces
called up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
