<HEADLINE> Thailand's Reserves Remain High: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh has denied reports that the country's reserves had
shrunk to 50 billion baht (1.72 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said on Thursday that the kingdom's reserves remain high at
240 billion baht (8.28 billion dollars) excluding tied-over funds.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to say whether the country would need loans
from abroad to ease liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week there were reports that the government needed
to borrow 10 billion U.S. dollars from abroad to bolster its
reserves.
</P>
<P>
The local press said Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya will visit
Japan next week to seek long-term low-interest credits, although
Thanong denied it.  
</P>
