<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Rupee Hits 7-month High Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India (RBI,
the central bank) has kept off the market even as the rupee
touched a seven-month high of 35.735 per U.S. dollar at the
interbank foreign exchange market in Bombay on Thursday due to
poor demand for the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
"They (RBI) made some inquiries, but did not come to the market
to buy dollars," the Times of India published here today quoted a
dealer at a foreign bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
The RBI inaction combined with the poor dollar demand pushed
the rupee up although supply was pretty normal, the dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the rupee traded at a high of 35.735 and a low of
35.765 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Trade was quite thin, with the market consisting of mainly of
sellers," said a dealer.
</P>
<P>
During Thursday's trading, according to dealers, a number of
banks were sitting on long dollar positions looking for the RBI to
come in and buy dollars.
</P>
<P>
As the rupee kept rising through the day and the RBI stayed
away, they were forced to unwind their positions which pushed the
rupee up.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the outlook for Friday was uncertain.
</P>
<P>
"It is a bit confusing," said a dealer. "Based on its past
actions, everyone expected the RBI to step in once the rupee hit
35.75 but now it is not clear what their intentions are."
</P>
<P>
"We will have to wait and see," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
