<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Better Off by Reclaiming Wasteland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Farmer Guo Qibao from the village
of Qianmajia in north China's Shanxi Province bought land-use
rights for 800 ha of barren hillside in 1993, and has cultivated
the acreage into productive farmland which last year earned him
200,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guo and six of his brothers are among the 122,000 families who
have benefited from the local government's practice to auction off
wasteland.
</P>
<P>
Luliang Prefecture, known for its poverty, has 310,000 ha of
wasteland, which accounts for 70 percent of its farmland. Local
farmers eked out a meager existence.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the prefecture adopted land-use policies, which
defined that the farmers' ownership of wasteland will remain
unchanged for 50 years, and buyers can put the land into market
and circulation.
</P>
<P>
Farmer Li Qiusheng in Linxian County raised 6,000 yuan to buy
some 66 ha of wasteland. After his purchase, his entire family was
kept busy on the land, growing fruit trees, herbal medicines, and
raising pigs and sheep.
</P>
<P>
Now the family earns more than 100,000 yuan annually. "The
State has good land-use policies, we should work to improve the
wasteland," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Farmers, rather than the State, are now the major investors in
developing wasteland, and a growing number of private
entrepreneurs are joining in.
</P>
<P>
By now, the prefecture has auctioned off around 233,000 ha of
wasteland, more than 60 percent of which has been improved, and a
million farmers are living a more prosperous life as a result.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
