<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Plans to Boost Forest Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar needs to turn out more
value-added forest products to meet domestic demand and promote
export, the official newspaper the New Light of Myanmar reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Forestry Minister Chit Swe made the proposal here Thursday at a
seminar on the Development of Wood-Based and Non-Wood Forest
Product Industries.
</P>
<P>
The minister said industries of value-added forest products
lack private investment, while entrepreneurs pay more attention to
export of logs and sawn timber as a short-term business.
</P>
<P>
He called for upgrading trading to manufacturing for the
long-term interest.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed establishing all-round wood-based industrial
zones as well as non-wood forest product industries with the aim
to scale down and cease export of logs.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's hardwood export in the 1996-97 fiscal year ending
March was estimated at 142,000 cubic meters, while that of teak at
184,000 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's export of forest products amounted to 218 million
U.S. dollars in the 1996-97 fiscal year, accounting for 24.4
percent of the total export, second only to agricultural export,
according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar restricts export of logs by banning the private sector
from exporting teak logs after the enactment of the country's
Forest Law in 1992. However, export of value-added wood products
is encouraged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
