<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Listed Railway Company Achieving Good Economic Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou-Shenzhen Railway
Co. Ltd. of south China's Guangdong Province has netted an
after-tax profit of 1.178 billion yuan since it began operating on
a share-holding system more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The company, which is also China's first firm ever listed on
the bourses both in Hong Kong and New York, has also topped other
Chinese railway companies in the areas of average per km
operational railway earnings, per capita pre-tax earnings and per
capita after-tax profit.
</P>
<P>
The company switched to its share-holding plan in March of
1966, when the country's railway sector was defeated by the
airlines in a fight for passengers.
</P>
<P>
An executive of the company said it had made a good use of its
greater autonomy in decision-making and practiced a wide range of
measures in daily operations that cater to market changes after
March, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The measures include optimizing time schedules for train
departures and arrivals, banning the collecting of miscellaneous
fees from passengers, which both have proved effective and helped
win over some of the company's lost market shares.
</P>
<P>
The company will strive to improve its internal operation
mechanisms, said the executive, added that it would use IC
(identity card) automatic ticket-selling machines in Guangzhou,
capital of Guangdong Province, and the city of Shenzhen to
increase speed of ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the company will also finish the
electrification of the existing Guangzhou-Shenzhen Railway Line
and use imported Sweden-made trains to shorten the present rail
travel time from Guangzhou to Shenzhen to 48 minutes in the first
half of next year, according to the executive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
