<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Combine Onshore With Offshore Oil Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The Suizhong 36-1 oilfield in
China's Bohai Sea has prepared an unprecedented move to combine
onshore with offshore oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
According to a Bohai Oilfield official, the purpose of the move
is to decrease production costs and shorten the time of
development.
</P>
<P>
Six offshore oil platforms and an oil and gas treatment plant
with an annual handling capacity of 5.5 million tons will be
built. Crude oil extracted from offshore oil wells will be
transported onshore for initial treatment and processing through a
70-km pipeline.
</P>
<P>
The Suizhong field is the country's largest offshore
oilfield. It is located at Liaodong Bay and covers a
48-sq.km. area with more than 300 million tons of proven oil
reserves.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the success of the program, the Bohai Oil Company
began a trial exploration project in 1988 at a cost of 1.8 billion
yuan, on a 6.55-sq. km. area.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 50 million tons of proven reserves have been
discovered in the trial area, with an annual crude production
capacity of 1.5 million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floating Baht to Set Large Thai Conglomerate into Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's industrial conglomerate
Siam Cement Group has said it could lose as much as 9.9 billion
baht (about 340 million U.S. dollars) if the baht weakens to 30
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
With 4 billion dollars in outstanding foreign loans, 25 percent
of them short-term, the group faces massive foreign exchange
losses if the baht continues its slide against the dollar,
according to Siam president Chumpol Nalamlieng.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's reference rate on Thursday was 29.075 baht
to the dollar, as against the 25.75 before the floating, down 12.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The 84-year-old group relied on a basket hedge to guard against
foreign exchange fluctuations for its foreign debts, a common
method where firms borrow funds in different currencies matching
the weighting used by the Bank of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Under the basket hedge, appreciation of the dollar against the
baht would be balanced by a depreciation in the yen, thus
canceling much of the financial impact of minor currency
fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
However, since the float of the baht on July 2, the currency
has weakened by 10-15 percent against nearly all currencies,
wreaking havoc on Siam Cement's basket hedge strategy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Educated Chinese Farmers Getting Away From Poverty Faster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Liu Fujin, a farmer in Xinxian
county in China's Henan Province, who used to be illiterate, has
become a major dispenser of advice for his fellow villagers.
</P>
<P>
Liu is one of a million illiterate farmers who have benefited
from an illiteracy-eradication project that began in the early
1980s to help the poor people of the Dabie Mountains, in the
southern part of the province.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of illiterate or semi-literate young and
middle-aged farmers there dropped from 37 to 4.9. A literate
farmer is expected to learn 1,500 Chinese characters, be able to
keep an account book, write simple articles, and read simple
technical materials.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, educated farmers have learned how to get away
from poverty and have become more aware of the market economy. The
mountainous Xinyang prefecture has seen the number of poor people
drop from 2.57 million in 1983 to 473,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
"Among the remainder of the poor farmers, 37 percent still
suffer from illiteracy, so education is the key to poverty
relief," said Zhang Yuxin, the director of the prefecture's
poverty relief office.
</P>
<P>
Every village in the prefecture has training classes, and the
heirs of the illiteracy-eradication program can attend the classes
for further study. About two million farmers have learned one or
two practical skills that have helped them further.
</P>
<P>
Farmers, who in the past relied primarily on the weather's
mood, now turn to science and technology for relief. In 1990, the
prefecture introduced the use of hybrid rice on 200,000 ha to
increase per-ha output. As a result, it ended the history of
bringing in grain from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Science and technology have contributed greatly to its
eight-fold increase in GDP, seven-fold in revenues, and tripled
incomes for farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
