<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb President Condemns SFOR Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Serb rotating President of
the Bosnian Presidency, Momcilo Krajisnik, Thursday condemned the
killing of a Serb former police officer by the Multinational
Stablization Force (SFOR).
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik also criticized the arrest of a Serb hospital head by
the SFOR, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported from Pale.
</P>
<P>
He asked for an immediate investigation into the affair, and
punishment for the responsible person. Measures should be taken
to guarantee that the similar affairs did not happen again, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Only by this means, could the regional peace be saved and the
Dayton peace accord, signed in December, 1995, be comprehensively
implemented, Krajisnik said.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik, who had agreed to send Serb citizens, shown to be
guilty, for trial before the international community, also
called on the guarantors of the Dayton accord, especially the
United States, to prevent the SFOR from arresting people in the
Bosnian Serb Republic of Srpska.
</P>
<P>
He asked the Bosnian Serbs to keep calm and not to take
retaliatory actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
