<HEADLINE> U.S. President on Would-be NATO Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United States President
Bill Clinton said here today that Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic should strengthen development and democracy.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived in Warsaw on Thursday for a 20-hour visit after
the Madrid Summit of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO). At the July 8-9 NATO summit, three countries, Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic, were invited to join the military
alliance.
</P>
<P>
They hope to become new members in April 1999, when the
organization marks its 50th anniversary of the Washington Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Poland was "very satisfied" with the fact that it was on the
first list of the countries to be accepted by NATO, said Polish
President Aleksander Kwasniewski at ceremony welcoming Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents held talks on the costs of the NATO eastward
expansion and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with Polish Prime Minister Wlodzimierz
Cimoszewicz, President Clinton urged Poland to play a more active
role in regional affairs and agreed to provide aid to the country,
which has been suffering from serious floods.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also held talks with
her Polish counterpart, Dariusz Rosari, on the fee that Poland has
to share when it joins NATO.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to leave for a visit to Romania on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
