<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Send Delegation to Meet Sihanouk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) has agreed to send an Indonesian delegation to
meet Cambodia's Prince Norodom Sihanouk as part of an effort to
seek a peaceful resolution to the armed conflict in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
They consider Sihanouk to be a key Cambodian figure, having a
charisma respected by the common people and the two warring
parties.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said ASEAN foreign
ministers also expected the delegation to meet with Hun Sen and
Norodom Ranariddh, leaders of the two conflicting parties.
</P>
<P>
"We will ask them to give us an opportunity to meet them as
soon as possible before the ASEAN ministerial-level meeting is
held in Malaysia." he said.
</P>
<P>
As for plans for Cambodia's membership in the association,
Alatas said: "Although ASEAN has decided to delay Cambodia's
membership in the association, that country's status as an
observer at ASEAN forums remains."
</P>
<P>
"We do not mean to eliminate Cambodia's opportunity to join
ASEAN but will only suspend it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Troops loyal to Cambodia's First Prime Minister Norodom
Ranariddh, and Second Prime Minister Hun Sen, exchanged gunfire
near the capital Phnom Penh when Hun Sen's troops demanded to
search military barracks under Ranariddh's control for illegal
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's unwieldy coalition government collapsed in violence
on Saturday when Hun Sen's forces moved against Ranariddh's men in
the capital. Ranariddh had left the country the previous day.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen declared Ranariddh's ousting on Sunday as his forces
consolidated their grip on the city and its outskirts, pushing
Ranariddh's men from their bases in and around the city.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh accused Hun Sen of a coup d'etat and urged the United
Nations Security Council on Thursday not to recognize any
government resulting from the weekend's coup, and to freeze aid to
Cambodia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
