<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeological Items Found in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-five items of
Mesoamerican origin dated between 1100 and 1200 A.D. have been
found in eastern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Anthropologist Mirna Ruiz of the National Institute of
Anthropology and History said the items were found in the Ecatepec
municipality 20 days ago when stonemasons were building a fountain
on the Mexico-Pachuca highway.
</P>
<P>
She said among them was a sculpture of the wine god Tezca
Tzoncaltl, and an anthropomorphic figure with a vase in his hands
to deposit the hearts of sacrificed persons.
</P>
<P>
The wine god, who would transform anyone getting close, was
considered to be evil in the legends.
</P>
<P>
The anthropologist said Ecatepec, site of the Tecolines cavern
where a painting of Quetzalcoatl -- the major god in Mexican
Indian culture -- was found, was the birthplace of Mexican
culture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
