<HEADLINE> Committee Asks for Grant to Fight Juvenile Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 10 (Xinhua) -- A committee of the United
States House of Representatives increased the allocation for
fighting juvenile crime, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bill, approved by the Appropriations Committee's Commerce,
Justice, State and Judiciary panel, focuses on the problem of
juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
It proposes spending 300 million U.S. dollars for new block
grants for arresting and incarcerating juveniles, and another 238
million dollars for programs to prevent juvenile crime. A pending
Senate bill calls for spending 500 million dollars in block grants
each year, of which 40 percent could be used for prevention
programs.
</P>
<P>
The House earlier also called for 500 million dollars in
juvenile crime block grants, but said none of it could be used for
prevention.
</P>
<P>
So far, none of the juvenile crime bills have become law.
</P>
