<HEADLINE> Tajikistan Moves Towards National Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The first session of the Tajik
National Reconciliation Committee ended here today with a
mutual-forgiveness document signed, and an amnesty law draft
adopted.
</P>
<P>
The documents were signed by Abdullo Nuri, chairman of the
committee and leader of the Tajik oppositions, and Abdulmadzhid
Dostiyev, first deputy chairman of the Tajik Supreme Assembly
(parliament). Russia' First Deputy Foreign Minister Boris
Pastukhov and a United Nations special envoy for the Tajik issue
witnessed the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Under the mutual-forgiveness document, the Tajik government and
the oppositions will release captives seized after military
conflicts broke out in 1992. The amnesty law draft will be
submitted to the assembly for consideration.
</P>
<P>
The national reconciliation committee will move to Dushambe,
capital of Tajikistan, and its job is expected to be completed
before the general elections slated for mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan has suffered a lot in military conflicts between the
government and the oppositions following the nation's independence
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Tajik government has speeded up reconciliation with the
oppositions since 1995, and signed an agreement on achieving
national peace and harmony, on June 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
