<HEADLINE> NATO Forces Kill Former Bosnian Serb Police Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) peacekeeping forces in Bosnia today killed a
former Bosnia Serb police chief and arrested a hospital director.
</P>
<P>
The police chief, Sima Drljacca, was shot dead in the chest in
a fish restaurant when he opened fire on peacekeepers trying to
arrest him, in the city of Prijedor, in northern Bosnian Serb
controlled territory.
</P>
<P>
"Indicted war criminal Sima Drljacca, former police chief in
Prijedor, opened fire on soldiers of the NATO-led Stabilization
Force (SFOR) as they approached for the purpose of detaining him,
" a NATO statement said.
</P>
<P>
"One of the SFOR soldiers was wounded in the process. Drljacca
was killed when fire was returned in self-defense," it added.
</P>
<P>
Prijedor hospital director, Micha Kraccev, was arrested on
charges of complicity in genocide against Bosnian Muslims and
Croats during the long ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
He would be handed over to the International Criminal Tribunal
for Former Yugoslavia and later extradited to the Hague to await
trial, NATO spokesman Major Chris Riley said in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
Drljacca was sacked as police chief last fall at the insistence
of NATO after he and his his men threatened a unit of Czech
peacekeepers with banned weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
