<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents Ready to Help Those in Need </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 11 (Xinhua) -- More people in China's largest
commercial center are making a contribution to public well-being
by giving a hand to people in need.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey, 67 percent of Shanghai's families
have made a donation to Project Hope, which was established by the
Chinese government as a charitable organization for helping
children in poverty-stricken areas with their education.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-six percent of these families have made donations for
people in disaster-stricken areas, and 62 percent have offered aid
to neighbors or colleagues.
</P>
<P>
About 160,000 of the city's residents donated blood last year,
something that is fairly new in China, gaining the title "Advanced
Blood Donation City" for Shanghai with a population of 125 million.
</P>
<P>
Hu Jia, a high-school English language teacher, has spent over
200 of his days off doing charitable work and has donated more
than 2,000 yuan, more than two months' salary to destitute
families over the past few years. "The value of my life lies in
helping others," he explains modestly.
</P>
<P>
Lu Rong, a woman who has suffered from a uremia disability but
who could not afford the cost of long-term treatment, received
more than 20,000 yuan in donations when her condition was made
known to the public.
</P>
<P>
"My life has been sustained by the love of many people," she
said, "and I'll help others whenever possible for the rest of my
life."  
</P>
</TEXT>
