<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Urgent Need for Hi-Tech Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- China has gone a step further in
the competitive ability of its industrial technology, but still
has a long march ahead of it to catch up to the world's technology
leaders, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
China's was ranked 26th in the world in terms of industrial
competitiveness last year by World Competitiveness Year Book 1996,
published by the Lausanne Institute of Management and Development
of Switzerland, up from 34th place in 1994.
</P>
<P>
And there is still a great need for further development of
technology in all sectors of the economy, the paper quoted Shi
Dinghuan, director of the State Science and Technology
Commission's Industrial Technology Department, as saying.
</P>
<P>
To upgrade enterprises' competitiveness, the commission has
begun a project nation-wide to improve certain enterprises. It
will set up technology-improvement centers in 1,000 key state
enterprises and a larger number of engineering research centers to
increase technology transfer among domestic enterprises. China now
has 56 engineering research centers.
</P>
<P>
The country also plans to add 500 promotion and development
centers to the current 100, which mainly serve medium and small
firms, especially township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China's science departments will develop new
technology and facilities used for manufacturing, controls, and
automation, and develop cleaner coal, new energy, nuclear power,
energy conservation, environmental protection, and quality
control, and will build high-speed railways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
