<HEADLINE> New Wheat Breeds Help Raise Output in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 11 (Xinhua) -- Scientists in northwest China's
Shaanxi province have produced several hundred new strains of
wheat, raising per unit yield from 100 to 300 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The scientists, at the Yanglin Agriculture and Science Center
of Xi'an, the provincial capital, also produced four of the six
new breeds of the largest growing areas in China, and which
allowed for an increase in wheat production of more than 100
billion kilograms.
</P>
<P>
"Bima No.1", which was the work of the late Zhao Hongzhang, a
famous agronomist, was once used on a growing area of more than 60
million acres, setting a world record for the size of wheat
growing area.
</P>
<P>
One researcher, Li Zhengsheng, the well-known geneticist and
wheat breeder, whose achievements have been recognized by
chromosome engineers elsewhere, successfully produced the
"Xiaoyan" wheat strains, with a per acre yield of 525 to 675
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 agronomists at Yanglin have been using new
technology to produce new wheat strains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
