<HEADLINE> Masterkova Qualifies for Athletics Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Svetlana Masterkova, the 1996
Atlanta Olympic double champion, comfortably claimed the women's
800m during the final day of Russia's athletics championships in
Tula, Russia on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Running on the country's best track, Masterkova came home in
four minutes 3.61 seconds in the meeting which is a qualifier for
next month's world championships in Athens. Runner-up Margarita
Marusova finished more than three seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
Yelena Romanova, the 1992 women's Olympic gold medalist in the
10,000m event, withdrew from competition at the last-minute citing
health problems.
</P>
<P>
She will miss the world championships as well as sprinter Irina
Privalova and Inna Lasovskaya, the 1997 indoor world champion in
the triple jump. Both have not yet recovered from serious
injuries.
</P>
<P>
The national championships were lacking in star quality as
about 30 top Russian athletes have already secured world
championships berths thanks to strong results in meetings earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
Hammer-thrower Vadim Khersontsev and 1992 Olympic pole-vaulting
champion Maxim Tarasov are among them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a number of strong results highlighted the
meeting. In the women's events Lyudmila Galkina reached 6.98
meters to set the world's best this year, while Tatyana Alekseyeva
clocked the season's second fastest time of 49.98 seconds in the
400 meters.
</P>
<P>
In the men's javelin Sergei Makarov threw for 83.56 meters -- a
national record in the championships. 
</P>
