<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican President Presents Plan to Attract Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican President Jose Maria
Figueres has proposed a plan for the Central American country to
attract high technology investment.
</P>
<P>
To be a small country with a privileged geographical position
and a situation of peace and tranquility, are three Costa Rican
characteristics that will attract foreign investment, said
Figueres Wednesday at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"The government is betting high to consolidate a true high
technology enterprises web, with vertical integration, that will
support each other and will pay high salaries," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
Figueres announced he will visit Singapore next month to
analyze the development process that has transformed that Asian
country into an important industrial center.
</P>
<P>
The biggest enterprise of the world manufacturing microchips,
Intel, announced the incoming installation in Costa Rica of a plant
with an investment of over 300 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other 22 service enterprises will install themselves around
Intel, said the president.
</P>
<P>
According to Figueres, the plan to attract high technology
companies includes the support of his government to local firms,
big or medium, to adapt their production processes to the needs of
the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
Other elements would be to promote a change in the country's
education system to reinforce the technical aspect.
</P>
<P>
"The country must prepare 10,000 Costa Ricans in 24 months in
the technical field" to supply the demand of specialized labor,
said Figueres.
</P>
<P>
The project demands the modernization of the country's
infrastructure, specially ports, communications, and a road
network. The president said he would favor a legislation that
would permit the transference of those installations to private
initiative.
</P>
<P>
Figueres said that Costa Rica per capita income is three or
four times above that of its Central American neighbors, so the
country cannot compete with low salaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
