<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Plans Land Check </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 11 (Xinhua) -- The central government will soon
investigate whether farmland near cities and in rural areas has
been used in the last seven years to build golf courses,
factories or other development not stipulated in land-use
regulations, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the central government put a one-year
freeze on non-agricultural land-use, and announced the move on
April 15, according to State Land Administration (SLA), China's
top land-use and control authority.
</P>
<P>
Between 1986 and 1995, about 75 million mu (about five million
hectares) of cultivated land was lost to non-agricultural purposes.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, developers have left large tracts of land idle or
used them inefficiently. Some construction has also been
duplicated.
</P>
<P>
SLA will soon send seven groups of investigators to various
areas to urge local government agencies to begin the checks. In
August, the administration, along with the Ministry of Supervision
and other relevant departments, will handle the remaining land
cases.
</P>
<P>
The investigation will be the largest since the
mid-1980s. Investigators will look into non-agricultural land use
between 1991 and April 14.
</P>
<P>
In urban areas, investigators will examine land used by a
variety of development zones, industrial and commercial projects,
and real estate projects, including golf courses.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, the investigation will include land used for
construction and expansion of townships and villages.
</P>
<P>
In the following weeks, the investigation will focus
on: Whether the land used for such projects is in line with local
land utilization plans; whether the land was used with official
approval and has completed legal formalities; illegal transfers,
leases or mortgages.
</P>
<P>
SLA officials said they hoped the investigation could help the
government know the exact amount of non-agricultural land-use.
</P>
<P>
This, they said, would be vital for the government to curb the
chronic problem of randomly-occupying land, further intensify land
administration and gain good experience in perfecting land-use
regulations, laws and policies.
</P>
<P>
The officials also made it clear that all land rashly approved
for non-agricultural projects by local officials exceeding their
authority between January 1 and April 14 will be invalid and those
who were responsible for such approval will by punished.
</P>
<P>
The SLA is studying possible problems that might arise in the
investigation and ways to deal with them, so officials who
illegally approve land or dispense with land wastefully, as well
sa other lawbreakers, will be held responsible for their
wrongdoings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
