<HEADLINE> Ukraine Lauds Special Partnership with NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine stepped into a new era of
development on Wednesday after it signed a special partnership
agreement with the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO),
Ukraine's First Foreign Minister, Anton Buteiko, said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint meeting here of the Ukrainian Social and
Political Center, the NATO Information Center and the Journalists'
Association, Buteiko said: "The agreement is an achievement of
Ukraine's foreign policy which is dedicated to promoting
integration with Europe."
</P>
<P>
Buteiko believed that the agreement, signed during NATO's
summit in Madrid, would provide Ukraine with chances to enhance
communication with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"Most NATO members are also EU countries," he said. "The EU is
an important factor in Ukraine's economic development."
</P>
<P>
However, some participants of the meeting challenged Buteiko,
noting the special partnership agreement was not in line with
Ukraine's status as a nonaligned nation.
</P>
<P>
"Nonalignment requires Ukraine to actively strengthen
cooperation with Europe," Buteiko answered. "When NATO expands
into Eastern Europe, Ukraine has to cooperate with NATO for the
sake of its security."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that NATO was a pan-European security
structure. "NATO will function best when all European countries
become its members," he claimed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
