said Rios after losing 6-3, 7-6 (7/3) to world No. 67 Juan
Viloca, a 24-year-old Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
World No. 6 Corretja took advantage of Pioline's aching right
arm, "over-used" during his run to last weekend's final at the
All England Club and a loss to Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
Spaniard Corretja, who leads the ATP Tour in claycourt
victories with 27 this year, reached the quarter-finals easily as
Pioline finally gave up after less than an hour of play.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman, ranked 23 in the world after his Grand Slam
performance, took treatment several times on court and had the
arm strapped early in the second set.
</P>
<P>
Unseeded German Nicolas Kiefer, a protege of Boris Becker and a
Wimbledon quarterfinalist, duplicated that round of eight
performance on the high-alttude clay 1,000 meters above sea level
as he defeated American Richey Reneberg 7-5, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Rain twice interrupted the proceedings in the day's last
second-round match. But in the end, seventh seed Alberto
Berasategui fought through three sets to score a 7-6 (7-2), 1-6,
7-5 win over Italian Renzo Furlan. 
