<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Chief Warns Against Pure Statistical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 10 (Xinhua) -- With almost all major European
countries apparently having great difficulties to meet the
stability standards for the single European currency, the head of
Germany's central bank said today that a purely statistical
interpretation of the single currency standards would be wrong.
</P>
<P>
Hans Tietmeyer, president of the German central bank, known as
the Bundesbank, said today that the 3 percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP) budgetary target was "a very important
indicator," but what was more important was the durability of
government consolidation policies, a reference to cost-cutting to
eliminate budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
He added that the overall economic health of a country should
be the prime consideration of its qualification for the common
currency, called the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) is targeting to launch the Euro on
January 1, 1999. In order to qualify for its membership, a country
is mainly required to bring its budget deficit to less than 3
percent of GDP and its overall national debt to less than 60
percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Luxemburg was the only EU country who met all the conditions
for the Euro last year. Germany and France, the two driving forces
behind the Euro project, are struggling to meet the deficit
target, largely because of the huge cost of financing the benefits
for their double-digit unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The difficulties to meet the Euro stardards have created an
open rift between Germany and France, with Paris favoring a
softening of the stardards and Bonn so far still insisting on
strict adherence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Mercantile Exchange Moves Into New Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The New York Mercantile Exchange
began its operation earlier this week in its brand-new building in
Lower Manhattan here, as a major event to celebrate its 125th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
The 16-story building is located on the picturesque eastern
bank of the Hudson River, which is just a stone's throw from the
exchange's previous home in the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
The spacious upper and lower trading floors are column-free and
equipped with high-tech facilities for buying and selling future
contracts of basically two types of commodities -- the precious
metals and energy, briefly referred to as NYMEX and COMEX. They
were previously traded under the same roof of the trading of
cotton, coffee and sugar.
</P>
<P>
Overlooking from the glass shielded gallery, each of the
trading floors is equal to the size of at least two basket ball
courts. The layout of the floors, covered with torn pieces of
paper, is almost the same as the old days, with several circular
pits being built with computer terminal and phone desks installed
around.
</P>
<P>
Each of the pits deals with the trading of one individual
commodity. Hundreds of traders gather around the pits, yelling at
each other with hand signals, almost in frenzied manner. "It's
just an open-cry trading system," Miss Maria Gonzalez, a press
officer, told the reporter.
</P>
<P>
The traders, in different colored jackets, scrawled prices on
scratch pads and threw them into the center of the pit where a
market employee would pick them up and punch time on them. Prices
are inputed into hand-held terminals and reflected to big display
boards on surrounding walls and transmitted to other cities of the
world through satellite circuits.
</P>
<P>
The merger of NYMEX and COMEX in the spring of 1994 made the
New York Mercantile Exchange the largest of its kind in the world.
Some market analysts have shortened the market history to the
phrase of "from egg to energy," simply because the market was
launched 125 years ago with the trading of butter and cheese.
</P>
<P>
With hundreds of products being traded in history, the
mercantile exchange has truly reflected different stages of the
U.S. economy. In addition to crude oil, heating oil, unleaded
gas and natural gas, COMEX was added a completely new product --
electricity -- on March 29, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The market continues to offer about 8,100 jobs for New York.
The seemingly chaotic trading action is under strict rules and
regulations, according to market officials. Each telephone has
access to as many as 64 voice lines with the punch of a button.
And each phone is continuously recorded, to provide a kind of
backup for future reference if disputes arise with customers.
</P>
<P>
The New York Stock Exchange has long expected for a removal or
an expansion for the lack of trading space after its 100 years of
operation. Traders and market administrators obviously expect to
revitalize the New York Mercantile Exchange with the launching of
the new building. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970711.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Drops on Call for Strong Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar ended mostly
weaker today after top German central bank officials surprised the
market by calling for a strong mark and Britain's central bank
increased interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The mark had been hitting a series of three-year lows against
the dollar and six-year lows against the pound for the past few
weeks, with no obvious signs of discontent from the Bundesbank.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of England's decision to raise its base lending rate
by a quarter percentage point to 6.75 percent had been widely
expected and initially caused a flurry of pound selling by traders
who wanted to secure profits from the currency's strength.
</P>
<P>
The dollar traded as low as 1.7461 marks in intraday dealings
before settling at 1.7515 marks in New York, down from 1.7599
marks Wednesday. The pound cost 1.6886 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6880 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the dollar cost 113.18 yen, up from 112.77 yen Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Other dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday: 1.4493
Swiss francs, down from 1.4580; 5.9220 French francs, down from
5.9430; 1,712.00 Italian lire, down from 1,717.25; 1.3739 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.3732. 
</P>
</TEXT>
